en Jobs Per $1 Invested Than Fossil Fuel Or Nuclear Jobs\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.heatisonline.org/contentserver/objecthandlers/index.cfm?ID=4637&amp;Method=Full\" target=\"_blank\">Renewable energy promotes US job growth better than investment in fossil fuels\r\n</a><strong>(RF: Direct source for last?)</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLinks to clean energy jobs? Green Jobs Philly? Idealist? Craigslist? Specific companies?\r\n\r\n[Meenal: this doesn\'t say much. OK to remove?] We\'re committed to promoting a cleaner, more sustainable future for the city of Philadelphia. Moreover, we believe in a plan that works for all communities, bringing healthy solutions to large and small businesses, neighborhoods, workers, students, senior citizens, and all Philadelphians interested in a higher quality of living.\r\n\r\n[Meenal: this doesn\'t say much. OK to remove?] On this page, you will find links to information and a diverse network of businesses and organizations with a brighter vision for the future. With your support, we believe Philadelphia can become a beacon for the twenty-first century, turning a city plagued by economic troubles into fertile ground for solutions that work for all.\r\n\r\n[Meenal: rest of this page should be moved to a post on resources or policy]\r\n<h4><strong>RESOURCES\r\nSolar, Batteries and Microgrids</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/solar\">Learn About Solar</a> (Energy Sage SunShot)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SOuyZWqhlNU\">How Photovoltaic (PV) Solar Works\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96WqrcK2OmM\">How Solar Thermal (Hot Water) Works\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-g49IYTKIkA\">Home Energy Management Systems\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.homeedison.com/\">HomeEdison Battery Backup System</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://phys.org/news/2015-03-solarcity-microgrids-tesla-batteries.html\">Tesla Home Battery System</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Community and Energy Cooperatives</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VG3OMfHNJf4\">Starting a Solar Cooperative\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.geo.coop/\">Grassroots Economic Organizing\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://theenergy.coop/\">The Energy Coop\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://communitypowernetwork.org/\">Community Solar Resource Network\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://city.milwaukee.gov/MilwaukeeShines#.VSVVfbqP14Y\">Milwaukee Shines Solar Program</a> - A model for city solar programs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Sustainability and Energy Efficiency</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.inference.eng.cam.ac.uk/sustainable/book/tex/sewtha.pdf\">Sustainable Energy - without the hot air, David JC MacKay</a> (PDF e-book, 12MB) - A book that objectively and comprehensively sets out the various alternative low-carbon pathways that are open to us in a form that is both highly readable and entertaining.\r\n<em>Energy Efficiency</em> <strong>(RF: Links Needed!)</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Available Programs, Financing and Policy</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/market/estimate/enter/\">Instant Solar Estimate Generator</a> (FREE - Energy Sage SunShot)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy12osti/54738.pdf\">The Solarize Guidebook (PDF)</a> - Community guide to collective purchasing of residential PV systems (SunShot Program)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.phila.gov/green//index.html\">Philadelphia Greenworks Plan\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.puc.pa.gov/filing_resources/issues_laws_regulations/act_129_information.asp\">PUC Act 129 Information\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.peco.com/Savings/ToolsandCalculators/Pages/default.aspx\">PECO Calculators\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://programs.dsireusa.org/rss/state/44\">DSIRE PA (Complete Program Availability) (RSS Feed)</a> (RF: To be refined)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://programs.dsireusa.org/system/program\">DSIRE Programs (PA filter needed)\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.dsireusa.org/resources/presentations-and-publications/\">DSIRE Presentations and Publications</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Go Renewable','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 03:53:32','2015-05-13 03:53:32','',28,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/28-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(245,2,'2015-05-13 04:02:13','2015-05-13 04:02:13','<h4>Be the Change... in how you use energy</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>conserve energy</li>\r\n	<li>use energy efficiently</li>\r\n	<li>switch to renewable electricity\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86703\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_89815\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.communityenergyinc.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Community Energy</a> - for your home, your business or your school from solar and wind farms in Northeast US</span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86072\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86071\" class=\"\"><a href=\"https://theenergy.coop/electricity\" target=\"_blank\">The Energy Co-op</a> - for your home or business, from wind farms in PA or solar installations in Philadelphia </span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86069\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86070\" class=\"\"><a href=\"https://ethicalelectric.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Ethical Electric</a> - for your home, from wind or solar farms</span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_85824\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_85823\" class=\"\"><a href=\"https://www.greenmountainenergy.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Green Mountain Energy</a> - </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>generate your own renewable electricity\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86041\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86057\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.brighteyesolar.com/\" target=\"_blank\">BrightEye Solar</a> - solar installers based out of Lancaster PA                      </span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_85859\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86040\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.solarcity.com/\" target=\"_blank\">SolarCity</a> - California-based company operating nationally                     </span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_85860\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86039\" class=\"\"><a href=\"https://www.sunedison.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Sun Edison</a> - national company with nearby offices in Pennsauken NJ                            </span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86037\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_86038\" class=\"\"><a href=\"http://www.firstsolar.com/\" target=\"_blank\">First Solar</a> - global company based out of Arizona with nearby offices in Bridgewater NJ</span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_83931\" dir=\"ltr\"><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_84893\"><a href=\"http://us.sunpower.com/ \" target=\"_blank\">Sun Power</a> - California-based company with nearby offices in Hamilton NJ                      </span></li>\r\n	<li id=\"yui_3_16_0_1_1429635703001_85430\"><a href=\"http://www.vivintsolar.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Vivant Solar</a> - Utah based company with nearby offices in Mt Laurel NJ</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>eat local food</li>\r\n	<li>think outside the car (walk, bike, transit, car-sharing)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4>Be the Change... in how you make a living</h4>\r\nEvidence shows that dollar for dollar, investments in energy efficiency, and in wind and solar energy, produce many times more jobs than investments in existing fossil fuel development. See links below to understand that <em>clean energy creates more &amp; better jobs</em>: <em>\r\n</em>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://thinkprogress.org/climate/2012/03/28/453122/fact-sheet-6-things-you-should-know-about-the-value-of-renewable-energy/\" target=\"_blank\">Six Things You Should Know About the Value of Renewable Energy\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://citizensclimatelobby.org/laser-talks/jobs-fossil-fuels-vs-renewables/\" target=\"_blank\">Jobs - Fossil Fuels vs Renewables\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://cleantechnica.com/2013/03/20/over-3-times-more-green-jobs-per-million-than-fossil-fuel-or-nuclear-jobs/\" target=\"_blank\">Over 3 Times More Green Jobs Per $1 Invested Than Fossil Fuel Or Nuclear Jobs\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.heatisonline.org/contentserver/objecthandlers/index.cfm?ID=4637&amp;Method=Full\" target=\"_blank\">Renewable energy promotes US job growth better than investment in fossil fuels\r\n</a><strong>(RF: Direct source for last?)</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLinks to clean energy jobs? Green Jobs Philly? Idealist? Craigslist? Specific companies?\r\n\r\n[Meenal: this doesn\'t say much. OK to remove?] We\'re committed to promoting a cleaner, more sustainable future for the city of Philadelphia. Moreover, we believe in a plan that works for all communities, bringing healthy solutions to large and small businesses, neighborhoods, workers, students, senior citizens, and all Philadelphians interested in a higher quality of living.\r\n\r\n[Meenal: this doesn\'t say much. OK to remove?] On this page, you will find links to information and a diverse network of businesses and organizations with a brighter vision for the future. With your support, we believe Philadelphia can become a beacon for the twenty-first century, turning a city plagued by economic troubles into fertile ground for solutions that work for all.\r\n\r\n[Meenal: rest of this page should be moved to a post on resources or policy]\r\n<h4><strong>RESOURCES\r\nSolar, Batteries and Microgrids</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/solar\">Learn About Solar</a> (Energy Sage SunShot)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SOuyZWqhlNU\">How Photovoltaic (PV) Solar Works\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=96WqrcK2OmM\">How Solar Thermal (Hot Water) Works\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-g49IYTKIkA\">Home Energy Management Systems\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.homeedison.com/\">HomeEdison Battery Backup System</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://phys.org/news/2015-03-solarcity-microgrids-tesla-batteries.html\">Tesla Home Battery System</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Community and Energy Cooperatives</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VG3OMfHNJf4\">Starting a Solar Cooperative\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.geo.coop/\">Grassroots Economic Organizing\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://theenergy.coop/\">The Energy Coop\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://communitypowernetwork.org/\">Community Solar Resource Network\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://city.milwaukee.gov/MilwaukeeShines#.VSVVfbqP14Y\">Milwaukee Shines Solar Program</a> - A model for city solar programs</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Sustainability and Energy Efficiency</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.inference.eng.cam.ac.uk/sustainable/book/tex/sewtha.pdf\">Sustainable Energy - without the hot air, David JC MacKay</a> (PDF e-book, 12MB) - A book that objectively and comprehensively sets out the various alternative low-carbon pathways that are open to us in a form that is both highly readable and entertaining.\r\n<em>Energy Efficiency</em> <strong>(RF: Links Needed!)</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Available Programs, Financing and Policy</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.energysage.com/market/estimate/enter/\">Instant Solar Estimate Generator</a> (FREE - Energy Sage SunShot)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy12osti/54738.pdf\">The Solarize Guidebook (PDF)</a> - Community guide to collective purchasing of residential PV systems (SunShot Program)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.phila.gov/green//index.html\">Philadelphia Greenworks Plan\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.puc.pa.gov/filing_resources/issues_laws_regulations/act_129_information.asp\">PUC Act 129 Information\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.peco.com/Savings/ToolsandCalculators/Pages/default.aspx\">PECO Calculators\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://programs.dsireusa.org/rss/state/44\">DSIRE PA (Complete Program Availability) (RSS Feed)</a> (RF: To be refined)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://programs.dsireusa.org/system/program\">DSIRE Programs (PA filter needed)\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.dsireusa.org/resources/presentations-and-publications/\">DSIRE Presentations and Publications</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Go Renewable','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 04:02:13','2015-05-13 04:02:13','',28,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/28-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(246,2,'2015-05-13 17:21:47','2015-05-13 17:21:47','The Democratic Primary is next Tuesday, May 19th.  Philadelphia Democrats will select the candidate virtually certain to become our next Mayor.  Of the 6 in the running, Jim Kenney rises to the top, both in our opinion and in recent polls.\r\n\r\nThe next most likely contender is Anthony Hardy Williams who has close ties to outside millionaires intent on the privatization of our schools as well as th<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-254 alignleft\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" />e Marcellus Shale Coalition, which employs his wife and has contributed to his campaign. Williams has also <a href=\"http://www.jvpphilly.org/media/2015/4/2/jvp-questions-anthony-williams-on-islamophobic-associates\" target=\"_blank\">refused to distance himself from anti-Muslim extremists</a>.\r\n\r\nWe believe that Williams is divisive and toxic to Philadelphia, but that he has a serious chance of winning if the vote is split between Kenney and other candidates with progressive politics. This would be tragic for Philadelphia in many ways, and would mark a turning from the green agenda of the Nutter administration backwards toward a 19th century vision of pollution, economic stagnation and accelerating climate catastrophe.\r\n\r\nThere has been some concern expressed in environmental circles about the presence of Phil Rinaldi, CEO of Philadelphia Energy Solutions, on Jim\'s Policy Committee. We also were concerned about this and asked for a meeting with Jim and his policy chief, which turned out to be extremely productive.\r\n\r\nOur team of representatives from interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business, all opposed to the dirty energy hub, new pipelines, dangerous oil trains, and fracking, found Kenney most willing to listen to us as we educated him and his team about the moral issues around climate change as well as the value of green investment over fossil fuel investment in creating jobs without sacrificing clean air, clean water and clean food.\r\n\r\nAs proof of this commitment, Jim has publicly committed to an <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-releases-environment-transportation-policy-paper\" target=\"_blank\">open and democratic process for our energy future</a> and has added a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-policy-committee\" target=\"_blank\">trio of extraordinary environmental advocates to his policy team</a>:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dr. Poune Saberi practices as an occupational &amp; environmental medicine physician, and serves on the boards of Physicians for Social Responsibility.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Professor Kenneth Lande has taught at the University of Pennsylvania since 1959. He is one of the most prestigious physicists in the US and is known for his extensive research on the impact of fossil fuel extraction and use on health, safety and the environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dianne Herrin is a green development champion with training and experience with LEED Operations and Maintenance, carbon accounting/reporting, municipal energy planning, energy master planning, and has ISO 50001 certification.</p>\r\nThese three advocates will be at the table when energy and economic development decisions are made in the Kenney administration.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the Kenney policy team included substantial input from us into a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/assets/uploads/general/21st-Century-Transportation-and-Environment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">new energy policy for Philadelphia</a>. We’re delighted with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nWith three world-class policy advisors with extensive policy background on his team, Kenney actually has the expertise and experience at his disposal to move on concrete, doable steps toward this goal. The policy doesn’t just talk about carbon reduction. It lays out specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to implement a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nWe believe this puts Kenney head and shoulders above the rest of the candidates, even those who claim to support green development but don\'t put forward specific plans and still maintain that a fossil fuel hub can be achieved without environmental sacrifice.\r\n\r\nA week before our crucial meeting with Jim and his team, <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\" target=\"_blank\">GRID magazine endorsed Nelson Diaz</a> for Mayor.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability, but found it understandable because Kenney\'s new appointments and policy had not become public. Now, there is no reason not to feel GREAT leaving the voting booth, not wasting a vote on a candidate who can\'t win, but propelling a true champion into office.\r\n\r\nLast we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  This primary could be won by a narrow margin, so remember that voting for Diaz is taking a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, the corporate candidate, financed by the fracking industry, school privatizers and anti-Muslim voices.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">make this the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nA few more points about Jim Kenney: He’s local, born, educated and lived all his life in Philly, and committed to all of its residents. Our local paper, <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">the Inquirer, wrote this</a> about him on May 7th: “Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.” Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article, <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>, explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\nHe’s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">Daily News editorial</a> wrote this: “Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.”\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />He listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT\r\nrights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!\r\n--\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','trash','open','open','','the-climate-election-in-philadelphia','','','2015-05-15 18:09:51','2015-05-15 22:09:51','',0,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/?p=246',0,'post','',3),(247,2,'2015-05-13 11:22:27','2015-05-13 11:22:27','As true intelligence is demonstrated by patient listening, mayoral candidate Jim Kenney has listened and has recently added a trio of forward thinking sustainable energy professionals to his policy team. Philadelphians respect an open and democratic process for our energy future and applaud Kenney’s action. Jim Kenney wants to see our city continue forward as a green and clean historic destination, thereby he has made carbon reduction a top priority.\r\n\r\nOn May 11th, the Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\nOn May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right. this\r\n\r\nOn May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>\r\n\r\nOn Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhat environmental groups have endorsed Jim Kenney for Mayor? 350Philly, Clean Water Action, Neighborhood Networks, PennEnvironment, Sierra Club. All working to stop the dirty energy hub, to stop pipelines, to stop explosive oil trains, to stop fracking.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate election - Kenney for Mayor','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 11:22:27','2015-05-13 11:22:27','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(248,2,'2015-05-13 12:14:01','2015-05-13 12:14:01','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 5 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of all 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nListens to the people. Even people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to preparing for climate disruption.\r\n\r\nAs true intelligence is demonstrated by patient listening, mayoral candidate Jim Kenney has listened and has recently added a trio of forward thinking sustainable energy professionals to his policy team. Philadelphians respect an open and democratic process for our energy future and applaud Kenney’s action. Jim Kenney wants to see our city continue forward as a green and clean historic destination, thereby he has made carbon reduction a top priority.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 11th, the Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"</li>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n	<li>On April 24th, GRID magazine <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">endorses Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think; not just because we helped craft it! And, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.</li>\r\n	<li>On Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGiven his evolution, several\r\n\r\nWhat environmental groups have endorsed Jim Kenney for Mayor? 350Philly, Clean Water Action, Neighborhood Networks, PennEnvironment, Sierra Club. All working to stop the dirty energy hub, to stop pipelines, to stop explosive oil trains, to stop fracking.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">This ought to be the Climate Change election</a>.  Let\'s make it one.  Vote for Kenney.\r\n\r\n- gather articles abt Kenney\r\n- show he listens and cares\r\n- show his evolution\r\n- list env orgs endorsing him\r\n- photo w muslim leaders\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 12:14:01','2015-05-13 12:14:01','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(249,2,'2015-05-13 12:21:39','2015-05-13 12:21:39','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nKenney listens to the people. Even people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to preparing for climate disruption.\r\n\r\nAs true intelligence is demonstrated by patient listening, mayoral candidate Jim Kenney has listened and has recently added a trio of forward thinking sustainable energy professionals to his policy team. Philadelphians respect an open and democratic process for our energy future and applaud Kenney’s action. Jim Kenney wants to see our city continue forward as a green and clean historic destination, thereby he has made carbon reduction a top priority.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 11th, the Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"</li>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n	<li>On April 24th, GRID magazine <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">endorses Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think; not just because we helped craft it! And, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.</li>\r\n	<li>On Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nGiven his evolution, several\r\n\r\nLooking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team.\r\n\r\nSo a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too.  And we\'ve worked with the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nWe\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050. And pleased too that Kenney\'s for an open &amp; democratic process for our energy future.  And that he agreed to add people we recommended to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist, and a clean energy person, right alongside Mr Rinaldi.\r\n\r\nWho are we? 350Philly, Clean Water Action, Neighborhood Networks, PennEnvironment, Interfaith Power &amp; Light, Sierra Club\r\n\r\nAll working to stop the dirty energy hub, to stop pipelines, to stop explosive oil trains, to stop fracking.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe\'s evolved. And stepping up to the times.  We can continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this the Climate Change election.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">This ought to be the Climate Change election</a>.  Let\'s make it one.  Vote for Kenney.\r\n\r\n- gather articles abt Kenney\r\n- show he listens and cares\r\n- show his evolution\r\n- list env orgs endorsing him\r\n- photo w muslim leaders\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 12:21:39','2015-05-13 12:21:39','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(250,2,'2015-05-13 14:46:09','2015-05-13 14:46:09','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nHow?\r\n\r\nHe\'s local.\r\n\r\nHe\'s experienced around City Hall. On May 11th, the Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\nHe listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.  True intelligence is surely demonstrated by patient listening.\r\n\r\nHe listened to us expounding on the moral issues around climate. About creating jobs as well as a clean air, clean water and clean food. About creating an open and democratic process for our energy future. And added a trio of professionals to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist and a clean energy person. We applaud his listening.\r\n\r\nA week earlier, GRID magazine endorsed <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think. And, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  Remember that voting for Diaz is stealing a vote from Kenney, and handing it to the Anthony Williams, financed by the fracking industry and anti-Muslim voices.  This was explained to me in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n	<li></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLooking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team. See the Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>.\r\n\r\nSo a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too.  And we\'ve worked with the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nWe\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050. And pleased too that Kenney\'s for an open &amp; democratic process for our energy future.  And that he agreed to add people we recommended to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist, and a clean energy person, right alongside Mr Rinaldi.\r\n\r\nWho are we? 350Philly, the Beehive Design Collective, Be the Change (Phila chapter), Call to the Bar, Clean Water Action, EDGE (Encouraging Development of a Green Economy), Interfaith Power &amp; Light (Phila chapter), Maypop Collective for Climate &amp; Economic Justice, Penn Environment, PHEW! a bike shop, Physicians for Social Responsibility, Practical Energy Solutions, Protecting our Waters, Sierra Club (PA chapter), Transition Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nAll working to stop the dirty energy hub, to stop pipelines, to stop explosive oil trains, to stop fracking. And to build a clean energy economy for our region.\r\n\r\nHe\'s evolved. And stepping up to the times.  We can continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 14:46:09','2015-05-13 14:46:09','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(251,2,'2015-05-13 14:58:31','2015-05-13 14:58:31','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nHe\'s local.  Born, schooled, and worked in this city.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>On May 7th, the Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a>: Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.</li>\r\n	<li>On May 3rd, Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHe\'s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\nHe listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nLooking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team. See the Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>.\r\n\r\nSo a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too. He listened to us expounding on the moral issues around climate. About creating jobs as well as a clean air, clean water and clean food. About creating an open and democratic process for our energy future. And added a trio of professionals to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist and a clean energy person. We applaud his listening.\r\n\r\nAnd we\'ve helped the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia. We\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nA week earlier, GRID magazine endorsed <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think.\r\n\r\nEXPLAIN HOW.\r\n\r\nAnd, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  Remember that voting for Diaz is stealing a vote from Kenney, and handing it to the Anthony Williams, financed by the fracking industry and anti-Muslim voices.  This was explained to me in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><em>Who are we? 350Philly, the Beehive Design Collective, Be the Change (Phila chapter), Call to the Bar, Clean Water Action, EDGE (Encouraging Development of a Green Economy), Interfaith Power &amp; Light (Phila chapter), Maypop Collective for Climate &amp; Economic Justice, Penn Environment, PHEW! a bike shop, Physicians for Social Responsibility, Practical Energy Solutions, Protecting our Waters, Sierra Club (PA chapter), Transition Philadelphia.</em></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complain about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!','the Climate election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 14:58:31','2015-05-13 14:58:31','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(252,2,'2015-05-13 15:16:47','2015-05-13 15:16:47','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\nHe\'s local.  Born, schooled, and worked in this city, so I hear. Our local paper, the Inquirer, what <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a> about him on May 7th: \"Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right\". Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a> explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\nHe\'s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\nHe listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nLooking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team. See the Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>.\r\n\r\nSo a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too. He listened to us expounding on the moral issues around climate. About creating jobs as well as a clean air, clean water and clean food. About creating an open and democratic process for our energy future. And added a trio of professionals to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist and a clean energy person. We applaud his listening.\r\n\r\nAnd we\'ve helped the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia. We\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nA week earlier, GRID magazine endorsed <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think. Because it doesn\'t just talk about carbon reduction. It refers to specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nAnd, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  Remember that voting for Diaz is stealing a vote from Kenney, and handing it to the Anthony Williams, financed by the fracking industry and anti-Muslim voices.  This was explained to me in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complain about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 15:16:47','2015-05-13 15:16:47','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(253,2,'2015-05-13 15:19:15','2015-05-13 15:19:15','Next Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\n<strong>He\'s local</strong>.  Born, schooled, and worked in this city, so I hear. Our local paper, the Inquirer, wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a> about him on May 7th: \"Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right\". Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a> explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\n<strong>He\'s experienced around City Hall.</strong> The recent May 11th Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"\r\n\r\n<strong>He listens.</strong>  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Looking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team. See the Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">So a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too. He listened to us expounding on the moral issues around climate. About creating jobs as well as a clean air, clean water and clean food. About creating an open and democratic process for our energy future. And added a trio of professionals to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist and a clean energy person. We applaud his listening.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">And we\'ve helped the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia. We\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.</p>\r\nA week earlier, GRID magazine endorsed <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think. Because it doesn\'t just talk about carbon reduction. It refers to specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nAnd, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  Remember that voting for Diaz is stealing a vote from Kenney, and handing it to the Anthony Williams, financed by the fracking industry and anti-Muslim voices.  This was explained to me in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complain about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 15:19:15','2015-05-13 15:19:15','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(254,2,'2015-05-13 16:11:10','2015-05-13 16:11:10','','kenney-m','','inherit','open','open','','kenney-m','','','2015-05-13 16:11:10','2015-05-13 16:11:10','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(255,2,'2015-05-13 16:12:48','2015-05-13 16:12:48','','kenney-a','','inherit','open','open','','kenney-a','','','2015-05-13 16:12:48','2015-05-13 16:12:48','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(256,2,'2015-05-13 16:13:33','2015-05-13 16:13:33','','kenney-u','','inherit','open','open','','kenney-u','','','2015-05-13 16:13:33','2015-05-13 16:13:33','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-u.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(257,2,'2015-05-13 16:15:35','2015-05-13 16:15:35','','James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540','','inherit','open','open','','james-kenney-city-council-flickr-940x540','','','2015-05-13 16:15:35','2015-05-13 16:15:35','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(258,2,'2015-05-13 16:17:01','2015-05-13 16:17:01','[caption id=\"attachment_257\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-257 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540-300x172.jpg\" alt=\"James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540\" width=\"300\" height=\"172\" /> photo courtesy kenney2015.com[/caption]\r\n\r\nNext Tuesday, May 19th, are the primaries.  Philadelphians, predominantly democratic, get to nominate one of the 6 democratic candidates for our next Mayor. The lineup includes Jim Kenney, Nelson Diaz, Lynne Abraham, Anthony Williams, and Doug Oliver &amp; Milton Street. Whoever wins in the primaries next week in effect becomes our next Mayor after the November elections. Of the 6, Jim Kenney rises to the top.\r\n\r\n<strong>He\'s local</strong>.  Born, schooled, and worked in this city, so I hear. Our local paper, the Inquirer, wrote <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">this</a> about him on May 7th: \"Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right\". Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a> explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\n<strong>He\'s experienced around City Hall.</strong> The recent May 11th Daily News <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">editorial</a> wrote this: \"Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.\"<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>He listens.</strong>  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Looking at recent polls, we felt Kenney had a winning chance of becoming our next Mayor. Except for the fact that he had Phil Rinaldi, the man behind the dirty energy hub plan, on his advisory team. See the Feb 26th Philadelphia Magazine article <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/citified/2015/02/26/heavy-hitters-jim-kenneys-new-policy-team\" target=\"_blank\">Heavy hitters in Jim Kenney\'s new policy team</a>.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">So a coalition of people against the dirty energy hub, against pipelines, against oil trains, and against fracking met with Kenney.  It was a team representing interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business too. He listened to us expounding on the moral issues around climate. About creating jobs as well as a clean air, clean water and clean food. About creating an open and democratic process for our energy future. And added a trio of professionals to his policy team: a public health person, a scientist and a clean energy person. We applaud his listening.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">And we\'ve helped the Kenney team to craft an energy policy for Philadelphia. We\'re pleased with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.</p>\r\nA week earlier, GRID magazine endorsed <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\">Nelson Diaz for Mayor</a>.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability.  We\'ve since realized that this was before the Kenney energy policy was public. The Kenney policy is much better, we think. Because it doesn\'t just talk about carbon reduction. It refers to specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!<img class=\"alignright wp-image-254 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" />\r\n\r\nAnd, last we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  Remember that voting for Diaz is stealing a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, financed by the fracking industry and anti-Muslim voices.  This was explained to me in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complain about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and make this <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 16:17:01','2015-05-13 16:17:01','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(259,2,'2015-05-13 17:09:40','2015-05-13 17:09:40','[caption id=\"attachment_257\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-257 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540-300x172.jpg\" alt=\"James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540\" width=\"300\" height=\"172\" /> photo courtesy kenney2015.com[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Democratic Primary is next Tuesday, May 19th.  Philadelphia Democrats will select the candidate virtually certain to become our next Mayor.  Of the 6 in the running, Jim Kenney rises to the top, both in our opinion and in recent polls.\r\n\r\nThe next most likely contender is Anthony Hardy Williams who has close ties to outside millionaires intent on the privatization of our schools as well as the Marcellus Shale Coalition, which employs his wife and has contributed to his campaign. Williams has also refused to distance himself from anti-Muslim extremists.\r\n\r\nWe believe that Williams is divisive and toxic to Philadelphia, but that he has a serious chance of winning if the vote is split between Kenney and other candidates with progressive politics. This would be tragic for Philadelphia in many ways, and would mark a turning from the green agenda of the Nutter administration backwards toward a 19th century vision of pollution, economic stagnation and accelerating climate catastrophe.\r\n\r\nThere has been some concern expressed in environmental circles about the presence of Phil Rinaldi, CEO of Philadelphia Energy Solutions, on Jim\'s Policy Committee. We also were concerned about this and asked for a meeting with Jim and his policy chief, which turned out to be extremely productive.\r\n\r\nOur team of representatives from interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business, all opposed to the dirty energy hub, new pipelines, dangerous oil trains, and fracking, found Kenney most willing to listen to us as we educated him and his team about the moral issues around climate change as well as the value of green investment over fossil fuel investment in creating jobs without sacrificing clean air, clean water and clean food.\r\n\r\nAs proof of this commitment, Jim has publicly committed to an open and democratic process for our energy future and has added a trio of extraordinary environmental advocates to his policy team:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dr. Poune Saberi is the section chief for Occupational and Environmental Medicine at Philadelphia VA Medical Center and clinical faculty at Hospital of University of Pennsylvania. She serves on the national and Philadelphia board of Physicians for Social Responsibility.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Professor Kenneth Lande has taught at the University of Pennsylvania since 1959. He is one of the most prestigious physicists in the US and is known for his extensive research on the impact of fossil fuel extraction and use on health, safety and the environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dianne Herrin, put forward by the Sustainable Business Alliance, is a green development champion with training and experience with LEED Operations and Maintenance, carbon accounting/reporting, municipal energy planning, energy master planning, and has ISO 50001 certification.</p>\r\nThese three advocates will be at the table when energy and economic development decisions are made in the Kenney administration.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the Kenney policy team included substantial input from us into a new energy policy for Philadelphia. We’re delighted with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nWith three world-class policy advisors with extensive policy background on his team, Kenney actually has the expertise and experience at his disposal to move on concrete, doable steps toward this goal. The policy doesn’t just talk about carbon reduction. It lays out specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to implement a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nWe believe this puts Kenney head and shoulders above the rest of the candidates, even those who claim to support green development but don\'t put forward specific plans and still maintain that a fossil fuel hub can be achieved without environmental sacrifice.\r\n\r\nA week before the crucial meeting with Jim and his team, GRID magazine endorsed Nelson Diaz for Mayor.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability, but found it understandable because the new appointments and policy had not become public. Now, there is no reason not to feel GREAT leaving the voting booth, not wasting a vote on a candidate who can\'t win, but propelling a true champion into office.\r\n\r\nLast we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  This primary could be won by a narrow margin, so remember that voting for Diaz is taking a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, the corporate candidate, financed by the fracking industry, school privatizers and anti-Muslim voices.  To put it in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">make this the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nA few more points about Jim Kenney: He’s local, born, educated and lived all his life in Philly, and committed to all of its residents. Our local paper, <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">the Inquirer, wrote this</a> about him on May 7th: “Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.” Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article, <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>, explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\nHe’s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">Daily News editorial</a> wrote this: “Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.”\r\n\r\nHe listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT <img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><img class=\"alignright wp-image-254 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" /></p>\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 17:09:40','2015-05-13 17:09:40','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(260,2,'2015-05-13 17:18:48','2015-05-13 17:18:48','[caption id=\"attachment_257\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-257 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540-300x172.jpg\" alt=\"James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540\" width=\"300\" height=\"172\" /> photo courtesy kenney2015.com[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Democratic Primary is next Tuesday, May 19th.  Philadelphia Democrats will select the candidate virtually certain to become our next Mayor.  Of the 6 in the running, Jim Kenney rises to the top, both in our opinion and in recent polls.\r\n\r\nThe next most likely contender is Anthony Hardy Williams who has close ties to outside millionaires intent on the privatization of our schools as well as th<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-254 alignleft\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" />e Marcellus Shale Coalition, which employs his wife and has contributed to his campaign. Williams has also <a href=\"http://www.jvpphilly.org/media/2015/4/2/jvp-questions-anthony-williams-on-islamophobic-associates\" target=\"_blank\">refused to distance himself from anti-Muslim extremists</a>.\r\n\r\nWe believe that Williams is divisive and toxic to Philadelphia, but that he has a serious chance of winning if the vote is split between Kenney and other candidates with progressive politics. This would be tragic for Philadelphia in many ways, and would mark a turning from the green agenda of the Nutter administration backwards toward a 19th century vision of pollution, economic stagnation and accelerating climate catastrophe.\r\n\r\nThere has been some concern expressed in environmental circles about the presence of Phil Rinaldi, CEO of Philadelphia Energy Solutions, on Jim\'s Policy Committee. We also were concerned about this and asked for a meeting with Jim and his policy chief, which turned out to be extremely productive.\r\n\r\nOur team of representatives from interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business, all opposed to the dirty energy hub, new pipelines, dangerous oil trains, and fracking, found Kenney most willing to listen to us as we educated him and his team about the moral issues around climate change as well as the value of green investment over fossil fuel investment in creating jobs without sacrificing clean air, clean water and clean food.\r\n\r\nAs proof of this commitment, Jim has publicly committed to an <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-releases-environment-transportation-policy-paper\" target=\"_blank\">open and democratic process for our energy future</a> and has added a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-policy-committee\" target=\"_blank\">trio of extraordinary environmental advocates to his policy team</a>:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dr. Poune Saberi practices as an occupational &amp; environmental medicine physician, and serves on the boards of Physicians for Social Responsibility.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Professor Kenneth Lande has taught at the University of Pennsylvania since 1959. He is one of the most prestigious physicists in the US and is known for his extensive research on the impact of fossil fuel extraction and use on health, safety and the environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dianne Herrin is a green development champion with training and experience with LEED Operations and Maintenance, carbon accounting/reporting, municipal energy planning, energy master planning, and has ISO 50001 certification.</p>\r\nThese three advocates will be at the table when energy and economic development decisions are made in the Kenney administration.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the Kenney policy team included substantial input from us into a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/assets/uploads/general/21st-Century-Transportation-and-Environment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">new energy policy for Philadelphia</a>. We’re delighted with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nWith three world-class policy advisors with extensive policy background on his team, Kenney actually has the expertise and experience at his disposal to move on concrete, doable steps toward this goal. The policy doesn’t just talk about carbon reduction. It lays out specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to implement a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nWe believe this puts Kenney head and shoulders above the rest of the candidates, even those who claim to support green development but don\'t put forward specific plans and still maintain that a fossil fuel hub can be achieved without environmental sacrifice.\r\n\r\nA week before our crucial meeting with Jim and his team, <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\" target=\"_blank\">GRID magazine endorsed Nelson Diaz</a> for Mayor.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability, but found it understandable because Kenney\'s new appointments and policy had not become public. Now, there is no reason not to feel GREAT leaving the voting booth, not wasting a vote on a candidate who can\'t win, but propelling a true champion into office.\r\n\r\nLast we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  This primary could be won by a narrow margin, so remember that voting for Diaz is taking a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, the corporate candidate, financed by the fracking industry, school privatizers and anti-Muslim voices.  To put it in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">make this the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nA few more points about Jim Kenney: He’s local, born, educated and lived all his life in Philly, and committed to all of its residents. Our local paper, <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">the Inquirer, wrote this</a> about him on May 7th: “Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.” Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article, <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>, explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\nHe’s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">Daily News editorial</a> wrote this: “Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.”\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />He listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT <img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />rights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!\r\n--\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"></p>\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 17:18:48','2015-05-13 17:18:48','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(261,2,'2015-05-13 17:19:49','2015-05-13 17:19:49','[caption id=\"attachment_257\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-257 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540-300x172.jpg\" alt=\"James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540\" width=\"300\" height=\"172\" /> photo courtesy kenney2015.com[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Democratic Primary is next Tuesday, May 19th.  Philadelphia Democrats will select the candidate virtually certain to become our next Mayor.  Of the 6 in the running, Jim Kenney rises to the top, both in our opinion and in recent polls.\r\n\r\nThe next most likely contender is Anthony Hardy Williams who has close ties to outside millionaires intent on the privatization of our schools as well as th<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-254 alignleft\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" />e Marcellus Shale Coalition, which employs his wife and has contributed to his campaign. Williams has also <a href=\"http://www.jvpphilly.org/media/2015/4/2/jvp-questions-anthony-williams-on-islamophobic-associates\" target=\"_blank\">refused to distance himself from anti-Muslim extremists</a>.\r\n\r\nWe believe that Williams is divisive and toxic to Philadelphia, but that he has a serious chance of winning if the vote is split between Kenney and other candidates with progressive politics. This would be tragic for Philadelphia in many ways, and would mark a turning from the green agenda of the Nutter administration backwards toward a 19th century vision of pollution, economic stagnation and accelerating climate catastrophe.\r\n\r\nThere has been some concern expressed in environmental circles about the presence of Phil Rinaldi, CEO of Philadelphia Energy Solutions, on Jim\'s Policy Committee. We also were concerned about this and asked for a meeting with Jim and his policy chief, which turned out to be extremely productive.\r\n\r\nOur team of representatives from interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business, all opposed to the dirty energy hub, new pipelines, dangerous oil trains, and fracking, found Kenney most willing to listen to us as we educated him and his team about the moral issues around climate change as well as the value of green investment over fossil fuel investment in creating jobs without sacrificing clean air, clean water and clean food.\r\n\r\nAs proof of this commitment, Jim has publicly committed to an <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-releases-environment-transportation-policy-paper\" target=\"_blank\">open and democratic process for our energy future</a> and has added a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-policy-committee\" target=\"_blank\">trio of extraordinary environmental advocates to his policy team</a>:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dr. Poune Saberi practices as an occupational &amp; environmental medicine physician, and serves on the boards of Physicians for Social Responsibility.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Professor Kenneth Lande has taught at the University of Pennsylvania since 1959. He is one of the most prestigious physicists in the US and is known for his extensive research on the impact of fossil fuel extraction and use on health, safety and the environment.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dianne Herrin is a green development champion with training and experience with LEED Operations and Maintenance, carbon accounting/reporting, municipal energy planning, energy master planning, and has ISO 50001 certification.</p>\r\nThese three advocates will be at the table when energy and economic development decisions are made in the Kenney administration.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the Kenney policy team included substantial input from us into a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/assets/uploads/general/21st-Century-Transportation-and-Environment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">new energy policy for Philadelphia</a>. We’re delighted with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nWith three world-class policy advisors with extensive policy background on his team, Kenney actually has the expertise and experience at his disposal to move on concrete, doable steps toward this goal. The policy doesn’t just talk about carbon reduction. It lays out specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to implement a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nWe believe this puts Kenney head and shoulders above the rest of the candidates, even those who claim to support green development but don\'t put forward specific plans and still maintain that a fossil fuel hub can be achieved without environmental sacrifice.\r\n\r\nA week before our crucial meeting with Jim and his team, <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\" target=\"_blank\">GRID magazine endorsed Nelson Diaz</a> for Mayor.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability, but found it understandable because Kenney\'s new appointments and policy had not become public. Now, there is no reason not to feel GREAT leaving the voting booth, not wasting a vote on a candidate who can\'t win, but propelling a true champion into office.\r\n\r\nLast we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  This primary could be won by a narrow margin, so remember that voting for Diaz is taking a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, the corporate candidate, financed by the fracking industry, school privatizers and anti-Muslim voices.  To put it in 2 words: Ralph Nader.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">make this the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nA few more points about Jim Kenney: He’s local, born, educated and lived all his life in Philly, and committed to all of its residents. Our local paper, <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">the Inquirer, wrote this</a> about him on May 7th: “Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.” Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article, <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>, explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\nHe’s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">Daily News editorial</a> wrote this: “Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.”\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />He listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT\r\nrights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!\r\n--\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 17:19:49','2015-05-13 17:19:49','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(262,2,'2015-05-13 18:22:38','2015-05-13 18:22:38','','SignPetitionsolar','','inherit','open','open','','signpetitionsolar','','','2015-05-13 18:22:38','2015-05-13 18:22:38','',154,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SignPetitionsolar.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(263,2,'2015-05-13 18:22:59','2015-05-13 18:22:59','Things to read and sign and share, all written by our team.\r\n\r\nOn 4/6/15, see Judy Wick’s guest post on <a href=\"http://foodandwaterwatch.org\" target=\"_blank\">Food &amp; Water Watch</a>\'s blog titled <a href=\"http://www.foodandwaterwatch.org/blogs/standing-up-for-philadelphias-sustainable-economy/\" target=\"_blank\">Standing up for Philadelphia\'s Sustainable Economy</a>. Judy is the founder of the <a href=\"http://www.whitedog.com\" target=\"_blank\">White Dog Café</a>. She also founded the <a href=\"http://sbnphiladelphia.org\" target=\"_blank\">Sustainable Business Network of Greater Philadelphia</a> and <a href=\"http://fairfoodphilly.org\" target=\"_blank\">Fair Food Philly</a>.\r\n\r\nOn 3/19/15, see <a href=\"https://www.ecasavesenergy.org\" target=\"_blank\">The Energy Coordinating Agency</a>\'s post titled <a href=\"https://www.ecasavesenergy.org/about/eca-news/we-have-plan-will-you-sign\" target=\"_blank\">We have a Plan. Will you Sign on?</a>, which lists the ECA’s <a href=\"https://www.ecasavesenergy.org/ecas-recommendations-next-mayor-philadelphia\" target=\"_blank\">Recommendations for the next Mayor of Philadelphia</a>, offering to \"Unleash The Power Of Energy Efficiency To Grow Philadelphia’s Economy And Create Local Jobs\".\r\n\r\nOn 3/5/15, Sam Bernhardt of Food &amp; Water Watch wrote this petition, titled <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1uHjY5NOPnhad7tNYXoHShD0xyMOvGrLx5k47nH3c_Tk/viewform\" target=\"_blank\">Protect Our Health and Safety From the Dirty Fossil Fuel Barrage!</a>','Actions - What you can do','','inherit','open','open','','154-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 18:22:59','2015-05-13 18:22:59','',154,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/154-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(264,2,'2015-05-13 18:31:33','2015-05-13 18:31:33','Great little video posted by <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/Street_Level_Living_with_a_refinery_in_South_Philly.html\" target=\"_blank\">Philly.com</a> with West Passyunk Neighbors Association Jennifer Harrison discussing living next door to the PES oil refinery in South Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nShe details how the monitoring station instructs local residents that they should drive less and consume less energy in order to breath cleaner air.  In a classic blame the victim mentality, the implication would be that the oil refined at PES is emitting vast amounts of particulate emissions each year and we are at fault for that because we drive and use light bulbs.\r\n\r\nOf course the truth is if everyone in Philadelphia stopped driving and using electricity tomorrow the amount of emissions from the refinery wouldn\'t lower by one particle, but we will still have to breath it in.\r\n\r\nThe video closing with Harrison asking the poignant question of how would the next mayor deal with the issues that are arising for people who have to live next door to an energy hub.\r\n\r\nThe article and video are part of a series about \"little things\" around Philly that never get fixed, and they are looking to talk to other leaders of RCO\'s about issues the next mayor should be made aware of.  All things clean air and refinery related would seem like perfect topics, so if you are an RCO or know an RCO have them contact Gregg Gethard at gregg_gethard@yahoo.com or call (215)854-2267.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Living Next Door to an Energy Hub','','inherit','open','open','','198-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 18:31:33','2015-05-13 18:31:33','',198,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/198-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(265,2,'2015-05-13 18:32:53','2015-05-13 18:32:53','I first met Rekha last February, when she too trudged in the snow and ice form Northwest Philadelphia into <a href=\"http://citycoho.com\" target=\"_blank\">City Coho</a>, to witness the formation of our coalition.  She returned to <a href=\"http://sch.org\" target=\"_blank\">SCH</a> (Springside Chestnut Hill Academy) and proceeded to organize the upcoming <a href=\"http://www.chestnuthilllocal.com/2015/04/15/sch-academy-student-to-host-girls-climate-summit/\" target=\"_blank\">Girl\'s Climate Summit</a>.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_179\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<a href=\"http://bpf2.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/REL_Climat-Summit.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-179\" src=\"http://bpf2.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/REL_Climat-Summit-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"photo courtesy Chestnut Hill Local\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a> photo courtesy Chestnut Hill Local[/caption]\r\n\r\nIn the process, it seems she\'s met some pretty interesting local groups. Like <a href=\"http://fairmountworks.com\" target=\"_blank\">Philadelphia Water Works</a>, the <a href=\"http://ecasavesenergy.org\" target=\"_blank\">Energy Coordinating Agency</a>, the <a href=\"https://www.fi.edu\" target=\"_blank\">Franklin Institute</a>, the Climate &amp; Urban Systems Partnership, <a href=\"http://protectingourwaters.wordpress.com\" target=\"_blank\">Protecting Our Waters</a>, the <a href=\"http://dvgbc.org\" target=\"_blank\">Delaware Valley Green Building Council,</a> as well as the Phila chapter of <a href=\"http://psrphila.org\" target=\"_blank\">Physicians for Social Responsibility</a>.\r\n\r\nFollow her at <a href=\"https://twitter.com/climategirls\" target=\"_blank\">@climategirls</a>!','Meet our young leader: Rekha Dhillon-Richardson','','inherit','open','open','','178-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 18:32:53','2015-05-13 18:32:53','',178,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/178-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(266,2,'2015-05-13 18:34:28','2015-05-13 18:34:28','Philadelphia City Councilman David Oh arranged for an event on the Drexel campus last Thursday. Titled <em>LNG Exports: Exploring the possibilities in Philadelphia</em>, it entailed a keynote presentation by Cheniere Energy, opportunities for the nation &amp; Philadelphia in LNG production &amp; export, plus 3 panels on LNG &amp; energy infrastructure, market analysis &amp; investment, site preparation.\n\n<img class=\" wp-image-175 size-medium aligncenter\" src=\"http://bpf2.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/IMG_0097-e1429449335795-300x101.jpg\" alt=\"LNG panel\" width=\"300\" height=\"101\" />\n\nHere\'s what we found about <a href=\"http://davidstockmanscontracorner.com/cheniere-energy-poster-boy-for-the-shale-gas-hallucination/\" target=\"_blank\">Cheniere Energy: Poster-boy For The Shale Gas Hallucination</a>, which, summarized, states that \"the shale gas story is not about an economic miracle, the wonders of technology, the prowess of job creators.  Instead, it\'s a place where the cheap capital enabled by central banks goes to die.\"\n\nSeveral residents went, and found that most of the attendees at this forum did not live in our region. That the panelists were likewise from all around the US. That there was no representation from public health professionals, nor any mention of public health.  Who will speak for the people? When citizens began questioning Councilman Oh, the reply was... I don\'t work for you. So the questions, and the attacks, on industry continued. And yes, security was called to protect industry from citizens, and one by one, the citizens were escorted out.\n\nSome of what happened was covered by the media. Jon Hurdle of StateImpactPA wrote <img class=\" wp-image-176 size-thumbnail alignright\" src=\"http://bpf2.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/IMG_0083-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"IMG_0083\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /><a href=\"http://stateimpact.npr.org/pennsylvania/2015/04/17/shale-gas-opponents-shout-down-industry-speaker-at-lng-session/\" target=\"_blank\">Shale Gas Opponents Shout Down Industry Speaker at Philadelphia LNG Session</a>; Andrew Maykuth of the Philadelphia Inquirer wrote <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/business/20150417_Anti-drilling_protest_interrupts_Drexel_energy_forum.html\" target=\"_blank\">Anti-drilling protest interrupts Drexel energy forum</a>; and someone from the Marcellus Drilling industry wrote <a href=\"http://marcellusdrilling.com/2015/04/peaceful-protesters-removed-from-lng-export-hearing-in-philly/\" target=\"_blank\">\"Peaceful\" Protesters Removed from LNG Export Hearing in Philly</a>.\n\nI do hope Councilman Oh heard us. And plans to gain a balanced education around this subject by inviting public health professionals and those in the renewable energy field to a future forum.  We, as citizens of greater Philadelphia, have concerns. Concerns about air quality from increased emissions. Concerns about water quality when we hear about a tunnel under the Delaware river. Concerns about pipelines coming through our properties, bringing the Marcellus gas into our region. Concerns about trains exploding from the increased volume of dirty fossil fuels headed our way.\n\nWe invite Councilman Oh, and all of City Council to look to the future. A future with reduced greenhouse gases, a future with solar panels or greenery on every roof, a future with fewer cars and more rapid transit, a bright green future for future generations. We can do it. We must do it.','Disruption at LNG Exports Talk','','inherit','open','open','','172-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 18:34:28','2015-05-13 18:34:28','',172,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/172-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(267,2,'2015-05-13 18:34:42','2015-05-13 18:34:42','Philly.com posted an <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-04-13/news/61108220_1_largest-oil-refinery-philadelphia-energy-solutions-pollution\">excellent article</a> yesterday which highlights how no-brainer the real choice over the debate about having a refinery within the confines of our city.  Good paying union jobs always sound great, however the price we are paying for them is jaw dropping.\n<blockquote>In 2013, according to the latest statistics available from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the site - the largest oil refinery on the East Coast - let loose 701,284 pounds (or more than 350 tons) of hazardous air pollutants, including roughly 29 tons of benzene, a potent carcinogen, and many more tons of other toxins that experts say can contribute to breathing problems such as asthma.</blockquote>\nThey also go on to highlight how these raw numbers translate into what happens when you live here.\n<blockquote>The continued pollution is a cause for concern for advocates and public-health experts alike, who note that Philadelphia has one of the highest rates of childhood asthma in the nation. Dr. Marilyn Howarth of the University of Pennsylvania\'s Center of Excellence in Environmental Toxicology said the asthma rate of about 26 percent among kids in some of the city\'s poorest neighborhoods is three times the national average.</blockquote>\nThere\'s more.\n<blockquote>\"The refinery has traditionally contributed a great deal of pollution to the Philadelphia region, and as the refinery operations increase . . . you can only reasonably expect these emissions to increase,\" Howarth said. The Philadelphia region currently fails to meet federal clean-air standards for ozone and small-particulate matter, two crucial pollution yardsticks.</blockquote>\nIt\'s even worse then that.\n<blockquote>An EPA analysis of South Philadelphia toxic pollution released last fall found that the vast majority of emissions in the neighborhood came from the refinery and that 11 percent - nearly 40 tons - were known carcinogens, largely benzene. The two biggest sources - roughly two-thirds of the total - were sulfuric acid and hydrogen cyanide.\n\n\"Those are acids,\" said Howarth of the sulfur-laced emissions, \"and they are very strong pollutants. They may not cause cancer, but they certainly contribute to asthma and would irritate the airways for people with chronic pulmonary disease.\"</blockquote>\nSo basically it\'s a pretty clear connection between having a refinery in our city and not having acceptable clean air, having huge rates of asthma, significant risks to children and the elderly and infirm especially and increased risks of cancer.\n\nWant to know how many jobs we get for all that?  845.  To put that into perspective TWU Local 234 is just one of 17 unions with SEPTA provides over 5000 jobs alone.\n\nThe article also quotes the man who is profiting vastly from endangering and harming so many (and who does not live near his refinery) Phil Rinaldi, CEO of Philadelphia Energy Solutions which runs the refinery.  He is sure that opposition to an energy hub in Philadelphia is rooted in \"naivete\" and that he clearly believes that society cannot endure without burning fossil fuels.\n\nHowever the actual truth is that society cannot operate for much longer <a href=\"http://www.skepticalscience.com/\">burning fossil fuels like we are now</a>, and the time for when this must end is shorter then most people realize.   This makes any further investment like pipelines and new refineries a terrible short sighted idea even ignoring the terrible health effects they clearly have.  Mr Rinaldi will likely deny this as long as he possibly can, however he is the one who is naive if he thinks Philadelphians will let him pollute our city and our bodies so he can become unimaginably wealthy in the process without a fight.  A really big fight.\n\n&nbsp;','845 jobs vs all of our lungs and the future of our city, world','','inherit','open','open','','214-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 18:34:42','2015-05-13 18:34:42','',214,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/214-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(268,2,'2015-05-13 18:35:31','2015-05-13 18:35:31','Despite reading, learning, talking about energy for the past several months, I just stumbled upon this blog post (<a href=\"http://www.greenphillyblog.com/sponsored-post/support-clean-local-energy-hub-choose-pa-wind-2015/\">Support a Clean, Local Energy Hub: Choose PA Wind in 2015</a>) by Julie Hancher of <a href=\"http://www.greenphillyblog.com\">GreenPhillyBlog</a> today.\n<blockquote>\"Yet Philadelphia doesn’t have to be an energy hub for natural gas and fossil fuels to be a powerhouse – we have the potential to be <em>a clean</em> energy hub right here.\"</blockquote>\nFelt it was an appropriate  start for this site. Great meeting you today, Julie, at the #goodeconomyphilly Twitter chat with City Council candidates.','Support a clean, local energy hub','','inherit','open','open','','44-revision-v1','','','2015-05-13 18:35:31','2015-05-13 18:35:31','',44,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/44-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(269,2,'2015-05-13 19:54:59','2015-05-13 19:54:59','[caption id=\"attachment_257\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-257 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540-300x172.jpg\" alt=\"James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540\" width=\"300\" height=\"172\" /> photo courtesy kenney2015.com[/caption]\n\nThe Democratic Primary is next Tuesday, May 19th.  Philadelphia Democrats will select the candidate virtually certain to become our next Mayor.  Of the 6 in the running, Jim Kenney rises to the top, both in our opinion and in recent polls.\n\nThe next most likely contender is Anthony Hardy Williams who has close ties to outside millionaires intent on the privatization of our schools as well as th<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-254 alignleft\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" />e Marcellus Shale Coalition, which employs his wife and has contributed to his campaign. Williams has also <a href=\"http://www.jvpphilly.org/media/2015/4/2/jvp-questions-anthony-williams-on-islamophobic-associates\" target=\"_blank\">refused to distance himself from anti-Muslim extremists</a>.\n\nWe believe that Williams is divisive and toxic to Philadelphia, but that he has a serious chance of winning if the vote is split between Kenney and other candidates with progressive politics. This would be tragic for Philadelphia in many ways, and would mark a turning from the green agenda of the Nutter administration backwards toward a 19th century vision of pollution, economic stagnation and accelerating climate catastrophe.\n\nThere has been some concern expressed in environmental circles about the presence of Phil Rinaldi, CEO of Philadelphia Energy Solutions, on Jim\'s Policy Committee. We also were concerned about this and asked for a meeting with Jim and his policy chief, which turned out to be extremely productive.\n\nOur team of representatives from interfaith groups, environmental groups, labor &amp; business, all opposed to the dirty energy hub, new pipelines, dangerous oil trains, and fracking, found Kenney most willing to listen to us as we educated him and his team about the moral issues around climate change as well as the value of green investment over fossil fuel investment in creating jobs without sacrificing clean air, clean water and clean food.\n\nAs proof of this commitment, Jim has publicly committed to an <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-releases-environment-transportation-policy-paper\" target=\"_blank\">open and democratic process for our energy future</a> and has added a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/media-releases/kenney-2015-policy-committee\" target=\"_blank\">trio of extraordinary environmental advocates to his policy team</a>:\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dr. Poune Saberi practices as an occupational &amp; environmental medicine physician, and serves on the boards of Physicians for Social Responsibility.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Professor Kenneth Lande has taught at the University of Pennsylvania since 1959. He is one of the most prestigious physicists in the US and is known for his extensive research on the impact of fossil fuel extraction and use on health, safety and the environment.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Dianne Herrin is a green development champion with training and experience with LEED Operations and Maintenance, carbon accounting/reporting, municipal energy planning, energy master planning, and has ISO 50001 certification.</p>\nThese three advocates will be at the table when energy and economic development decisions are made in the Kenney administration.\n\nIn addition, the Kenney policy team included substantial input from us into a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/assets/uploads/general/21st-Century-Transportation-and-Environment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">new energy policy for Philadelphia</a>. We’re delighted with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\n\nWith three world-class policy advisors with extensive policy background on his team, Kenney actually has the expertise and experience at his disposal to move on concrete, doable steps toward this goal. The policy doesn’t just talk about carbon reduction. It lays out specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to implement a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\n\nWe believe this puts Kenney head and shoulders above the rest of the candidates, even those who claim to support green development but don\'t put forward specific plans and still maintain that a fossil fuel hub can be achieved without environmental sacrifice.\n\nA week before our crucial meeting with Jim and his team, <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\" target=\"_blank\">GRID magazine endorsed Nelson Diaz</a> for Mayor.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability, but found it understandable because Kenney\'s new appointments and policy had not become public. Now, there is no reason not to feel GREAT leaving the voting booth, not wasting a vote on a candidate who can\'t win, but propelling a true champion into office.\n\nLast we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  This primary could be won by a narrow margin, so remember that voting for Diaz is taking a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, the corporate candidate, financed by the fracking industry, school privatizers and anti-Muslim voices.\n\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">make this the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\n\nA few more points about Jim Kenney: He’s local, born, educated and lived all his life in Philly, and committed to all of its residents. Our local paper, <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">the Inquirer, wrote this</a> about him on May 7th: “Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.” Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article, <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>, explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\n\nHe’s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">Daily News editorial</a> wrote this: “Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.”\n\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />He listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT\nrights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\n\nVote Kenney for Mayor!\n--\n\n&nbsp;','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-13 19:54:59','2015-05-13 19:54:59','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/13/246-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(270,2,'2015-05-13 19:58:20','2015-05-13 19:58:20','[caption id=\"attachment_257\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-257 size-medium\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540-300x172.jpg\" alt=\"James-Kenney-City-Council-Flickr-940x540\" width=\"300\" height=\"172\" /> photo courtesy kenney2015.com[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe Democratic Primary is next Tuesday, May 19th.  Philadelphia Democrats will select the candidate virtually certain to become our next Mayor.  Of the 6 in the running, Jim Kenney rises to the top, both in our opinion and in recent polls.\r\n\r\nThe next most likely contender is Anthony Hardy Williams who has close ties to outside millionaires intent on the privatization of our schools as well as th<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-254 alignleft\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-m-300x156.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-m\" width=\"300\" height=\"156\" />e Marcellus Shale Coalition, which employs his wife and has contributed to his campaign. Williams has also <a href=\"http://www.jvpphilly.org/media/2015/4/2/jvp-questions-anthony-williams-on-islamophobic-associates\" target=\"_blank\">refused to distance himself from anti-Muslim extremists</a>.\r\n\r\nWe believe that Williams is divisive and toxic to Philadelphia, but that he has a serious chance of winning if the vote is split between Kenney and other candidates with progressive politics. This would be tragic for Philadelphia in many ways, and would mark a turning from the green agenda of the Nutter administration backwards toward a 19th century 