planning, and has ISO 50001 certification.</p>\r\nThese three advocates will be at the table when energy and economic development decisions are made in the Kenney administration.\r\n\r\nIn addition, the Kenney policy team included substantial input from us into a <a href=\"https://kenney2015.com/assets/uploads/general/21st-Century-Transportation-and-Environment.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">new energy policy for Philadelphia</a>. We’re delighted with the result, which includes a goal of 80% carbon reduction by 2050.\r\n\r\nWith three world-class policy advisors with extensive policy background on his team, Kenney actually has the expertise and experience at his disposal to move on concrete, doable steps toward this goal. The policy doesn’t just talk about carbon reduction. It lays out specific policy to reduce building energy use, to reduce the emissions from the City fleet, to implement a green (and local) procurement program, to incentivize renewable energy, to encourage more green roof infrastructure, and more!\r\n\r\nWe believe this puts Kenney head and shoulders above the rest of the candidates, even those who claim to support green development but don\'t put forward specific plans and still maintain that a fossil fuel hub can be achieved without environmental sacrifice.\r\n\r\nA week before our crucial meeting with Jim and his team, <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/4/24/grid-endorses-nelson-diaz-for-mayor.html\" target=\"_blank\">GRID magazine endorsed Nelson Diaz</a> for Mayor.  Many of us were disappointed to see this from a local magazine educating our region on sustainability, but found it understandable because Kenney\'s new appointments and policy had not become public. Now, there is no reason not to feel GREAT leaving the voting booth, not wasting a vote on a candidate who can\'t win, but propelling a true champion into office.\r\n\r\nLast we heard, Diaz only had 4% at the polls.  This primary could be won by a narrow margin, so remember that voting for Diaz is taking a vote from Kenney, and handing it to Anthony Williams, the corporate candidate, financed by the fracking industry, school privatizers and anti-Muslim voices.\r\n\r\nWe could continue wringing our hands and complaining about inaction on climate and corruption from our politicians. Or we can engage in conversation with them, and <a href=\"http://www.theecologist.org/blogs_and_comments/commentators/2851231/this_ought_to_be_the_climate_change_election_so_why_isnt_it.html\" target=\"_blank\">make this the Climate Change election it ought to be</a>.\r\n\r\nA few more points about Jim Kenney: He’s local, born, educated and lived all his life in Philly, and committed to all of its residents. Our local paper, <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-05-07/news/61869256_1_jim-kenney-police-brutality-civilian-review-board\" target=\"_blank\">the Inquirer, wrote this</a> about him on May 7th: “Kenney called passionate, loyal to a fault, driven to do right.” Earlier, on May 3rd, a Philadelphia Magazine article, <a href=\"http://www.phillymag.com/news/2015/05/03/jim-kenney-mayor-endorsement/\" target=\"_blank\">The (New) Jim Kenney for Mayor</a>, explained his evolution from an impassioned young man to a seasoned politician.\r\n\r\nHe’s experienced around City Hall. The recent May 11th <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/mayor/20150511_DN_Editorial__DAILY_NEWS_ENDORSEMENT__FOR_MAYOR__JIM_KENNEY.html\" target=\"_blank\">Daily News editorial</a> wrote this: “Kenney has shown himself to be independent, especially when you consider the lack of support for many of his pet causes. He knows how the city and its politics work, and is smart and open to new ideas.”\r\n\r\n<img class=\" size-medium wp-image-255 alignright\" src=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/kenney-a-300x169.jpg\" alt=\"kenney-a\" width=\"300\" height=\"169\" />He listens.  Even to people different from him. Examples abound in his openness to LGBT\r\nrights, to marijuana reform, to immigration reform. And now, to dealing with climate disruption in our region.\r\n\r\nVote Kenney for Mayor!\r\n--\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','the Climate Election in Philadelphia','','inherit','open','open','','246-revision-v1','','','2015-05-14 16:42:06','2015-05-14 16:42:06','',246,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/14/246-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(273,1,'2015-05-15 20:58:45','2015-05-16 00:58:45','These are the organizations that make up our coalition, which is fighting against the proposed dirty energy hub, and for a just, green and democratic Philadelphia:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://350philly.weebly.com/\" target=\"_blank\">350 Philadelphia</a></li>\r\n	<li>Beehive Collective in Kensington</li>\r\n	<li>Be the Change, Philadelphia chapter</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://calltothebar.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Call to the Bar</a>, led by Phila attorney Steve Harvey, inviting all attorneys to step up to work on climate change</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://cleanair.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Clean Air Council</a>, founded in 1967, now with 8000 members</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://cleanwateraction.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Clean Water Action</a>, founded in 1972, now with 1,000,000 members</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://delawareriverkeeper.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Delaware Riverkeeper Network</a>, established in 1988</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/edgephilly?fref=ts\" target=\"_blank\">EDGE</a> (Encouraging Development of a Green Economy)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://ecasavesenergy.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Energy Coordinating Agency</a>, founded in the early ’80s</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://foodandwaterwatch.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Food &amp; Water Watch</a>, established in 2005</li>\r\n	<li>Philadelphia chapter of <a href=\"http://paipl.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Pennsylvania Interfaith Power &amp; Light</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://maypopcollective.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Maypop Collective</a> for Climate and Economic Justice</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://momscleanairforce.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Mom’s Clean Air Force</a>, and their naptime activism around climate change, with 410,000 members nationally and over 17,000 members in PA</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://pennenvironment.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Penn Environment</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://phillyew.com/\" target=\"_blank\">PHEW! a bike shop</a>, getting people out of cars and onto bikes since 2009\r\nPhiladephia Jewish Climate Action Network</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://psrphila.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Physicians for Social Responsibility, Philadelphia</a> chapter</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://practicalenergy.net/\" target=\"_blank\">Practical Energy Solutions</a>\r\nPraxis Building Solutions &amp; the Sustainability Nexus at CityCoho</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://protectingourwaters.wordpress.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Protecting Our Waters</a>, founded in 2009, with over 4000 members</li>\r\n	<li>Sierra Club’s Pennsylvania chapter</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://sbnphiladelphia.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Sustainable Business Network of Greater Philadelphia</a> (SBN)</li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://transitionphilly.wordpress.com/\" target=\"_blank\">Transition Philadelphia</a>, inviting all Philadelphians to transition to a low-carbon relocalized economy.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;','Our Coalition','','inherit','open','open','','110-revision-v1','','','2015-05-15 20:58:45','2015-05-16 00:58:45','',110,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/15/110-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(275,1,'2015-05-24 11:36:42','2015-05-24 15:36:42','Our least favorite local resident, the PES refinery in South Philly, was seen <a href=\"http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/breaking/Refinery-Fire-Philadelphia-304767901.html\">belching black smoke</a> from a fire that broke out there on Saturday.\r\n\r\nPES spokesperson helpfully points out that the fire was contained to the refinery, but of course neglected to mention the heavy black smoke which was dispersed all across the city.  They were less helpful in describing what additional emissions Philadelphia residents were exposed to as a result of this and the other \"incidents\" this year, however in their defense they probably don\'t know and mostly don\'t live near the facility anyway so it\'s not really their problem.\r\n\r\nIf you are curious what emissions to  expect from the refinery during so-call normal operations (because 3 times in 5 months is not regular enough), please feel free to be horrified about what you have to breath everyday from this helpful <a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/air/tribal/pdfs/presentationpetroleumrefineries14Dec11.pdf\">EPA document</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','For 3rd time in 5 months refinery bellows black smoke across Philly','','publish','open','open','','for-3rd-time-in-5-months-refinery-bellows-black-smoke-across-philly','','','2015-06-01 20:54:26','2015-06-02 00:54:26','',0,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/?p=275',0,'post','',0),(276,1,'2015-05-24 18:00:25','2015-05-24 22:00:25','Our least favorite local resident, the PES refinery in South Philly, was seen <a href=\"http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/breaking/Refinery-Fire-Philadelphia-304767901.html\">belching black smoke</a> from a fire that broke out there on Saturday.\r\n\r\n[embed_media file=\"http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/portableplayer/?cmsID=304770521&amp;videoID=DMgdh33Imdlr&amp;origin=nbcphiladelphia.com&amp;sec=news&amp;subsec=breaking&amp;width=600&amp;height=360\" style=\"responsive\" width=\"640\" height=\"360\" soundcloud_visual=\"true\"][/embed_media]\r\n\r\nPES spokesperson helpfully points out that the fire was contained to the refinery, but of course neglected to mention the heavy black smoke which was dispersed all across the city.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Third time in 5 months refinery bellows black smoke across Philly','','inherit','open','open','','275-revision-v1','','','2015-05-24 18:00:25','2015-05-24 22:00:25','',275,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/24/275-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(277,1,'2015-05-24 18:11:12','2015-05-24 22:11:12','Our least favorite local resident, the PES refinery in South Philly, was seen <a href=\"http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/breaking/Refinery-Fire-Philadelphia-304767901.html\">belching black smoke</a> from a fire that broke out there on Saturday.\r\n\r\nPES spokesperson helpfully points out that the fire was contained to the refinery, but of course neglected to mention the heavy black smoke which was dispersed all across the city.  They were less helpful in describing what additional emissions Philadelphia residents were exposed to as a result of this and the other \"incidents\" this year, however in their defense they probably don\'t know and mostly don\'t live near the facility anyway so it\'s not really their problem.\r\n\r\nIf you are curious what emissions to  expect from the refinery during so-call normal operations (because 3 times in 5 months is not regular enough), please feel free to be horrified about what you have to breath everyday from this helpful <a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/air/tribal/pdfs/presentationpetroleumrefineries14Dec11.pdf\">EPA document</a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','For 3rd time in 5 months refinery bellows black smoke across Philly','','inherit','open','open','','275-revision-v1','','','2015-05-24 18:11:12','2015-05-24 22:11:12','',275,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/24/275-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(278,1,'2015-05-26 21:21:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','open','open','','','','','2015-05-26 21:21:25','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/?p=278',0,'post','',0),(279,1,'2015-05-28 06:32:52','2015-05-28 10:32:52',' ','','','publish','open','open','','279','','','2015-05-28 06:32:52','2015-05-28 10:32:52','',0,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/?p=279',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(280,1,'2015-05-28 13:00:09','2015-05-28 17:00:09','<a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/home\" target=\"_blank\">Penn Environment</a> organized a <a href=\"http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/local/item/82442-where-philly-stands-in-solar-power-and-the-push-for-more-state-funding\" target=\"_blank\">rally</a> at the IBEW Local 98 Union Headquarter\'s yesterday highlighting both groups support for Governor Wolf\'s alternative energy plan.  The proposed Wolf budget looks to bring back $50 million in solar power incentives which were cut from the PA Sunshine Program under the previous Corbett administration and to spend $225 million overall for clean energy in the state.\r\n\r\nSpeaking at the rally, <a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/staff/pae/david-masur\" target=\"_blank\">David Masur</a> executive director of PennEnvironment, drew attention to the groups recent <a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/reports/pae/shining-cities\" target=\"_blank\">Shining Cities report</a> where Philadelphia\'s ranked a disappointing 41st of 65 in per capita solar generation.\r\n\r\nJohn Hanger, Gov. Wolf\'s policy chief said at the rally...\r\n<blockquote>\"Solar power is going to reshape the energy industry across the United States, And the question for Pennsylvania is, are we going to lead, or are we actually going to be at the back of the pack?\"</blockquote>\r\nAlso speaking was Johnny \"Doc\" Dougherty, head of Local 98 and Philadelphia power broker.  He hedged that he was not there to \"give you a lecture on climate change\" but he pointed out recent evidence that our climate is in crisis.  He also stated that his union will work to ensure the provisions are back in this year\'s budget and encouraged everyone to <a href=\"http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/findyourlegislator/\" target=\"_blank\">call your state representative</a> to ask them to do the same.\r\n\r\nThe rally also shows the potential alliance between progressive environmental groups and traditional democratic unions.  It was this alliance that was also important in electing Governor Wolf and in helping Jim Kenney recently win the Democratic nomination for the mayor of Philadelphia.','Union and environmental groups rally to support governor\'s solar proposal','','publish','open','open','','union-and-environmental-groups-call-for-pressure-to-support-governors-solar-proposal','','','2015-05-28 13:23:36','2015-05-28 17:23:36','',0,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/?p=280',0,'post','',1),(281,1,'2015-05-28 11:56:36','2015-05-28 15:56:36','','3272423901_d26ffce5f8_z','','inherit','open','open','','3272423901_d26ffce5f8_z','','','2015-05-28 11:56:36','2015-05-28 15:56:36','',280,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/3272423901_d26ffce5f8_z.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(282,1,'2015-05-28 13:00:09','2015-05-28 17:00:09','<a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/home\" target=\"_blank\">Penn Environment</a> organized a <a href=\"http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/local/item/82442-where-philly-stands-in-solar-power-and-the-push-for-more-state-funding\" target=\"_blank\">rally</a> at the IBEW Local 98 Union Headquarter\'s yesterday highlighting both groups support for Governor Wolf\'s alternative energy plan.  The proposed Wolf budget looks to bring back $50 million in solar power incentives which were cut from the PA Sunshine Program under the previous Corbett administration and to spend $225 million overall for clean energy in the state.\r\n\r\nSpeaking at the rally, <a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/staff/pae/david-masur\" target=\"_blank\">David Masur</a> executive director of PennEnvironment, drew attention to the groups recent <a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/reports/pae/shining-cities\" target=\"_blank\">Shining Cities report</a> where Philadelphia\'s ranked a disappointing 41st of 65 in per capita solar generation.\r\n\r\nJohn Hanger, Gov. Wolf\'s policy chief said at the rally...\r\n<blockquote>\"Sola