ies report</a> where Philadelphia\'s ranked a disappointing 41st of 65 in per capita solar generation.\n\nJohn Hanger, Gov. Wolf\'s policy chief said at the rally...\n<blockquote>\"Solar power is going to reshape the energy industry across the United States, And the question for Pennsylvania is, are we going to lead, or are we actually going to be at the back of the pack?\"</blockquote>\nAlso speaking was Johnny \"Doc\" Dougherty, head of Local 98 and Philadelphia power broker.  He hedged that he was not there to \"give you a lecture on climate change\" but he pointed out recent evidence that our climate is in crisis.  He also stated that his union will work to ensure the provisions are back in this year\'s budget and encouraged everyone to <a href=\"http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/findyourlegislator/\" target=\"_blank\">call your state representative</a> to ask them to do the same.\n\nThe rally also shows the potential alliance between progressive environmental groups and traditional democratic unions.  It was this alliance that was also important in electing Governor Wolf and in helping Jim Kenney recently win the','Union and environmental groups rally to support governor\'s solar proposal','','inherit','open','open','','280-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-28 13:23:17','2015-05-28 17:23:17','',280,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/280-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(284,1,'2015-05-28 13:23:36','2015-05-28 17:23:36','<a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/home\" target=\"_blank\">Penn Environment</a> organized a <a href=\"http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/local/item/82442-where-philly-stands-in-solar-power-and-the-push-for-more-state-funding\" target=\"_blank\">rally</a> at the IBEW Local 98 Union Headquarter\'s yesterday highlighting both groups support for Governor Wolf\'s alternative energy plan.  The proposed Wolf budget looks to bring back $50 million in solar power incentives which were cut from the PA Sunshine Program under the previous Corbett administration and to spend $225 million overall for clean energy in the state.\r\n\r\nSpeaking at the rally, <a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/staff/pae/david-masur\" target=\"_blank\">David Masur</a> executive director of PennEnvironment, drew attention to the groups recent <a href=\"http://www.pennenvironment.org/reports/pae/shining-cities\" target=\"_blank\">Shining Cities report</a> where Philadelphia\'s ranked a disappointing 41st of 65 in per capita solar generation.\r\n\r\nJohn Hanger, Gov. Wolf\'s policy chief said at the rally...\r\n<blockquote>\"Solar power is going to reshape the energy industry across the United States, And the question for Pennsylvania is, are we going to lead, or are we actually going to be at the back of the pack?\"</blockquote>\r\nAlso speaking was Johnny \"Doc\" Dougherty, head of Local 98 and Philadelphia power broker.  He hedged that he was not there to \"give you a lecture on climate change\" but he pointed out recent evidence that our climate is in crisis.  He also stated that his union will work to ensure the provisions are back in this year\'s budget and encouraged everyone to <a href=\"http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/findyourlegislator/\" target=\"_blank\">call your state representative</a> to ask them to do the same.\r\n\r\nThe rally also shows the potential alliance between progressive environmental groups and traditional democratic unions.  It was this alliance that was also important in electing Governor Wolf and in helping Jim Kenney recently win the Democratic nomination for the mayor of Philadelphia.','Union and environmental groups rally to support governor\'s solar proposal','','inherit','open','open','','280-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 13:23:36','2015-05-28 17:23:36','',280,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/280-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(285,2,'2015-05-28 20:52:25','2015-05-29 00:52:25','<ol>\n	<li>To provide an educational resource for the public on the developments of the proposed fossil fuel energy hub.</li>\n	<li>To identify and propose solutions for an alternative energy hub centered on renewable, sustainable energy.</li>\n	<li>To make as many people in Greater Philadelphia aware of the immediate health, safety and economic impacts of a fossil fuel energy hub as possible, and to build popular support for responsible, sustainable and economically just alternatives.</li>\n</ol>','Our Goals','','inherit','open','open','','63-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 20:52:25','2015-05-29 00:52:25','',63,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(286,2,'2015-05-28 20:52:33','2015-05-29 00:52:33','Our Mission is to identify and promote practical plans for building a thriving and equitable regional economy that promotes full employment and secure, living-wage jobs while protecting the health and safety of our neighborhoods.  We believe this is best achieved through an open, transparent and deeply democratic process that puts the future of our city in the hands of the people who live and work here, not distant corporations and their political operatives.','Our Mission','','inherit','open','open','','59-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 20:52:33','2015-05-29 00:52:33','',59,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/59-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(287,2,'2015-05-28 20:52:48','2015-05-29 00:52:48','We take a bottom-up approach that focuses on building relationships between people with similar goals in order to catalyze self-organization and action. Our goal is to educate the people in their circles to facilitate positive change in their neighborhoods and communities, resulting in carbon neutral (or negative), locally governed, resilient and regenerative communities.','Our Vision','','inherit','open','open','','61-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 20:52:48','2015-05-29 00:52:48','',61,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/61-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(288,2,'2015-05-28 20:53:53','2015-05-29 00:53:53','','About Us','','inherit','open','open','','208-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 20:53:53','2015-05-29 00:53:53','',208,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/208-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(289,2,'2015-05-28 21:02:48','2015-05-29 01:02:48','Peoples Energy Solutions believes that now is the time to ramp up investment in our wealth of community-based solutions, rather than corporate deals which cut jobs and put more money in the hands of those who are not invested in the health and well-being of our neighborhoods.\n\nPhiladelphia is home to an abundance of talent, imagination, and proven successes when it comes to sustainability. We know that we have everything we need to be the great city we can be--world class institutions of culture, medicine and higher learning; a diverse and willing workforce; a network of sustainable and ethical businesses ready to grow and invest locally; and countless neighborhood groups, faith communities and civic associations ready to mobilize people to work together for the common good.\n\nWith your support, we believe Philadelphia can become a beacon for the twenty-first century, turning a city plagued by economic troubles into fertile ground for solutions that work for all.\n\n--\n\nBright Philly Future advocates for investment in our wealth of community-based solutions, rather than corporate deals which cut jobs and put more money in the hands of those who are not invested in the health and well-being of our neighborhoods.\n\nWe know that people are tired of politics as usual; tired of back-room deals; tired of our voices being ignored; tired of our health and safety being put at risk by polluters; tired of unemployment, underemployment and poverty wage jobs; tired of the “school to prison pipeline” that leaves our youth undereducated, unemployed and swept off the streets and into an out of control system of mass incarceration; and tired of being told that the half-measures and empty promises put on the table by corporate looters are our only choice.\n\nWe can have more stable, living-wage jobs and shared prosperity without a dirty fossil fuel “energy hub, ” without doubling down on dangerous, explosive trains of fracked shale oil rumbling through our densely populated neighborhoods, and without the toxic air and water pollution that fuel the asthma epidemic that already affects almost one quarter of our children.\n\nTo learn more about the plan to turn Philadelphia into an environmental sacrifice zone (sometimes referred to as “Houston on the Delaware”) click here (Link to “what is the fossil fuel energy hub and why do we oppose it?”)','What we stand for','','inherit','open','open','','68-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:02:48','2015-05-29 01:02:48','',68,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/68-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(290,2,'2015-05-28 21:03:28','2015-05-29 01:03:28','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBright Philly Future advocates for investment in our wealth of community-based solutions, rather than corporate deals which cut jobs and put more money in the hands of those who are not invested in the health and well-being of our neighborhoods.\r\n\r\nWe know that people are tired of politics as usual; tired of back-room deals; tired of our voices being ignored; tired of our health and safety being put at risk by polluters; tired of unemployment, underemployment and poverty wage jobs; tired of the “school to prison pipeline” that leaves our youth undereducated, unemployed and swept off the streets and into an out of control system of mass incarceration; and tired of being told that the half-measures and empty promises put on the table by corporate looters are our only choice.\r\n\r\nWe can have more stable, living-wage jobs and shared prosperity without a dirty fossil fuel “energy hub\", without doubling down on dangerous, explosive trains of fracked shale oil rumbling through our densely populated neighborhoods, and without the toxic air and water pollution that fuel the asthma epidemic that already affects almost one quarter of our children.\r\n\r\nTo learn more about the plan to turn Philadelphia into an environmental sacrifice zone (sometimes referred to as “Houston on the Delaware”) click here (Link to “what is the fossil fuel energy hub and why do we oppose it?”)','What we stand for','','inherit','open','open','','68-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:03:28','2015-05-29 01:03:28','',68,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/68-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(291,2,'2015-05-28 21:06:24','2015-05-29 01:06:24','<h4>PEOPLE POWER, LOCAL CONTROL</h4>\n<em>Bright Philly Future</em> proposes a resilient, green energy plan that puts people, not corporations in charge of our vital natural resources and public infrastructure.\n<h4>INVESTMENT IN PROVEN SLOUTIONS</h4>\nPhiladelphia is home to an abundance of talent, imagination, and proven successes when it comes to sustainability. Hard-working Philadelphians have already laid the groundwork of the imagination for our next era, and the solutions we need are right in front of us. We believe that the key to the future of Philadelphia lies in investment in practical, proven, community-based solutions, rather than corporate deals which cut jobs and exist only to siphon off more wealth into the hands of those who are not invested in the future of our communities.\n<h4>LEADERSHIP FROM THE GROUND UP</h4>\nWith the right leadership, these solutions will work for everybody, improving the health of communities, creating jobs, expanding public services, and turning Philadelphia into a national leader for the twenty-first century. <em>Bright Philly Future</em> is committed to being your guide to these ideas and the organizations who are working to make them reality.\n<h4>TRANSPARENCY</h4>\nWe believe that the future direction of our city should be decided through an open and transparent process, not in closed-door meetings between powerful economic interests and select politicians.\n<h4>DEMOCRACY AND EQUALITY</h4>\nWe believe in an economy that works for everyone, not just a privileged few, a plan that puts equal justice, living wage jobs, clean air and water, and public safety ahead of corporate profits.\n<h4>POLITICAL WILL</h4>\nWe know that the technology already exists to meet our energy needs responsibly, without sacrificing health and safety or contributing to catastrophic climate change, and that the only thing standing in our way is the lack of political will to wholeheartedly embrace a sustainable future. Our purpose is to create that will!\n<h4>COMMUNITY PARTICIPATION</h4>\nWe welcome input from responsible businesses, neighborhood associations, working families, students, senior citizens, and all Philadelphians interested in building a future that is just, sustainable, healthy and secure.\n\n<strong>Gardening</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uG2eHQ9Q078\">Permaculture: A Quiet Revolution\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m9y53sa\">About Permaculture\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m9y53sa\">What Your Garden Can Teach About Cities\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.appropedia.org/Aquaponics\">About Aquaponics\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.richsoil.com/hugelkultur/\">Hugelculture - An Advanced Raised Bed\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/k76y48w\">New study shows how trees clean the air in London</a></li>\n</ul>\n<strong>Transportation</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/ou2lnax\">Study of vehicle emissions will aid urban sustainability efforts\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/oy4gtem\">Inexpensive Electric Cars May Arrive Sooner Than You Think</a></li>\n	<li><strong>Community Capital\n</strong><a href=\"http://timebanks.org/more-about-timebanking/\">Time Banking</a>\n<a href=\"http://ilsr.org/\">Institute for Local Self-Reliance</a><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uG2eHQ9Q078\">\n</a><a href=\"http://transitiontownmedia.org/about-us/what-is-transition-town-media/\">Transition Town (Media, PA)</a>\n<a href=\"https://www.transitionnetwork.org/about\">Transition Network\n</a><a href=\"http://planphilly.com/\">Plan Philly\n</a><a href=\"http://www.phillynn.org/home/default.php\">Philadelphia Neighborhood Networks </a>(RF: Too political?)</li>\n</ul>','What we propose','','inherit','open','open','','70-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:06:24','2015-05-29 01:06:24','',70,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/70-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(292,2,'2015-05-28 21:07:13','2015-05-29 01:07:13','<h4>PEOPLE POWER, LOCAL CONTROL</h4>\r\n<em>Bright Philly Future</em> proposes a resilient, green energy plan that puts people, not corporations in charge of our vital natural resources and public infrastructure.\r\n<h4>INVESTMENT IN PROVEN SLOUTIONS</h4>\r\nPhiladelphia is home to an abundance of talent, imagination, and proven successes when it comes to sustainability. Hard-working Philadelphians have already laid the groundwork of the imagination for our next era, and the solutions we need are right in front of us. We believe that the key to the future of Philadelphia lies in investment in practical, proven, community-based solutions, rather than corporate deals which cut jobs and exist only to siphon off more wealth into the hands of those who are not invested in the future of our communities.\r\n<h4>LEADERSHIP FROM THE GROUND UP</h4>\r\nWith the right leadership, these solutions will work for everybody, improving the health of communities, creating jobs, expanding public services, and turning Philadelphia into a national leader for the twenty-first century. <em>Bright Philly Future</em> is committed to being your guide to these ideas and the organizations who are working to make them reality.\r\n<h4>TRANSPARENCY</h4>\r\nWe believe that the future direction of our city should be decided through an open and transparent process, not in closed-door meetings between powerful economic interests and select politicians.\r\n<h4>DEMOCRACY AND EQUALITY</h4>\r\nWe believe in an economy that works for everyone, not just a privileged few, a plan that puts equal justice, living wage jobs, clean air and water, and public safety ahead of corporate profits.\r\n<h4>POLITICAL WILL</h4>\r\nWe know that the technology already exists to meet our energy needs responsibly, without sacrificing health and safety or contributing to catastrophic climate change, and that the only thing standing in our way is the lack of political will to wholeheartedly embrace a sustainable future. Our purpose is to create that will!\r\n<h4>COMMUNITY PARTICIPATION</h4>\r\nWe welcome input from responsible businesses, neighborhood associations, working families, students, senior citizens, and all Philadelphians interested in building a future that is just, sustainable, healthy and secure.\r\n\r\n<strong>Gardening</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uG2eHQ9Q078\">Permaculture: A Quiet Revolution\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m9y53sa\">About Permaculture\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m9y53sa\">What Your Garden Can Teach About Cities\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.appropedia.org/Aquaponics\">About Aquaponics\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.richsoil.com/hugelkultur/\">Hugelculture - An Advanced Raised Bed\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/k76y48w\">New study shows how trees clean the air in London</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Transportation</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/ou2lnax\">Study of vehicle emissions will aid urban sustainability efforts\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/oy4gtem\">Inexpensive Electric Cars May Arrive Sooner Than You Think</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Community Capital\r\n</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://timebanks.org/more-about-timebanking/\">Time Banking</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://ilsr.org/\">Institute for Local Self-Reliance</a><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uG2eHQ9Q078\">\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://transitiontownmedia.org/about-us/what-is-transition-town-media/\">Transition Town (Media, PA)</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://www.transitionnetwork.org/about\">Transition Network\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://planphilly.com/\">Plan Philly\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.phillynn.org/home/default.php\">Philadelphia Neighborhood Networks</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n--','What we propose','','inherit','open','open','','70-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:07:13','2015-05-29 01:07:13','',70,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/70-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(293,2,'2015-05-28 21:08:59','2015-05-29 01:08:59','<strong></strong>Bright Philly Future grew out of a coalition that came together in response to the news of a December 5, 2014 closed-door conference bringing wealthy investors and representatives of international corporations together to lay plans for turning our city into an “Energy Hub.” This “Energy Hub” would be a receiving, processing and exporting center for some of the most damaging fossil fuel products known.\n\nWorking together, we realized that we share an alternative vision of Philadelphia as a Clean Energy Hub, a vibrant, dynamic, just and democratic city, a beacon for the 21st century. The solutions to our many concerns–about jobs, opportunity, public health, clean air and water, and social and economic justice–are right in front of us.\n\n--\n\nOur coalition initially came together in response to the news of a December 5, 2014 closed-door conference bringing wealthy investors and representatives of international corporations together to lay plans for turning our city into an “Energy Hub.” This \"Energy Hub\" would be a receiving, processing and exporting center for some of the most damaging fossil fuel products known. A dirty fossil fuel “energy hub” means doubling down on dangerous, explosive trains of fracked shale oil rumbling through our densely populated neighborhoods, doubling down on toxic air and water pollution and doubling down on asthma and respiratory diseases that already affect almost one quarter of our children and constitute a public health crisis.\n\nTo learn more about the plan to turn Philadelphia into an environmental sacrifice zone (sometimes referred to as “Houston on the Delaware\") click here (<span style=\"color: #0000ff;\">Link to “what is the fossil fuel energy hub and why do we oppose it?”)</span>\n\nWe know that people are tired of politics as usual; tired of back-room deals; tired of our voices being ignored; tired of our health and safety being put at risk by polluters; tired of unemployment, underemployment and poverty wage jobs; tired of the “school to prison pipeline” that leaves our youth undereducated, unemployed and swept off the streets and into an out of control system of mass incarceration; and tired of being told that the half-measures and empty promises put on the table by corporate looters are our only choice.','What brings us together','','inherit','open','open','','72-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:08:59','2015-05-29 01:08:59','',72,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/72-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(294,2,'2015-05-28 21:10:07','2015-05-29 01:10:07','<strong></strong><em>Bright Philly Future</em> grew out of a coalition that came together in response to the news of a December 5, 2014 closed-door conference bringing wealthy investors and representatives of international corporations together to lay plans for turning our city into an “Energy Hub”. This “Energy Hub” would be a receiving, processing and exporting center for some of the most damaging fossil fuel products known.\r\n\r\nWorking together, we realized that we share an alternative vision of Philadelphia as a Clean Energy Hub, a vibrant, dynamic, just and democratic city, a beacon for the 21st century. The solutions to our many concerns–about jobs, opportunity, public health, clean air and water, and social and economic justice–are right in front of us.\r\n\r\n--\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','What brings us together','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:10:07','2015-05-29 01:10:07','',72,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/72-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(295,2,'2015-05-28 21:11:43','2015-05-29 01:11:43','Our purpose is to:\n\nEDUCATE you about what is at stake, the science, economics and politics of clean energy vs. fossil fuels,\nEMPOWER you to take practical steps now to conserve energy, save money &amp; live a healthier life,\nENCOURAGE you to get involved and connect with organizations working on neighborhood, city-wide or national levels to bring about people-powered change.','Our purpose','','inherit','open','open','','74-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:11:43','2015-05-29 01:11:43','',74,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/74-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(296,2,'2015-05-28 21:12:01','2015-05-29 01:12:01','Our purpose is to:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>EDUCATE you about what is at stake, the science, economics and politics of clean energy vs. fossil fuels,</li>\r\n	<li>EMPOWER you to take practical steps now to conserve energy, save money &amp; live a healthier life,</li>\r\n	<li>ENCOURAGE you to get involved and connect with organizations working on neighborhood, city-wide or national levels to bring about people-powered change.</li>\r\n</ul>','Our purpose','','inherit','open','open','','74-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:12:01','2015-05-29 01:12:01','',74,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/74-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(297,2,'2015-05-30 21:09:00','2015-05-31 01:09:00','“Going green” is about transitioning to a healthier, cleaner, more livable city, while growing stable, living wage jobs and opportunities for all, built on proven, readily available, clean energy technologies. In contrast, the dirty fossil fuel “Energy Hub” plan is about turning back the clock to the 19th century, and writing off our city as an environmental “sacrifice zone” for the short-term profit of some of the worst corporate polluters on the planet.\n\nAs residents of Philadelphia, we need to\n<ol>\n	<li>change our City\'s role in the energy marketplace,</li>\n	<li>strengthen incentives for energy efficient &amp; renewable improvements,</li>\n	<li>strengthen disclosure requirements for commercial &amp; residential buildings, and</li>\n	<li>consider financing mechanisms for green projects that address market failures.  <b>\n</b></li>\n</ol>\nHere are some ideas\n<h4>1. Change our City\'s role in the energy marketplace</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><b>Municipal (group) power purchasing/ community choice aggregation\n</b>Communities participating in the Sustainable Westchester coalition are going to be able to purchase power as a municipal group and offer it to their citizens.  People can choose to participate and purchase from the town, or stay in the usual arrangement and buy from the utility.   More <a href=\"http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/albany/2015/02/8563054/state-approves-westchester-power-experiment\">here</a>. Philadelphia could investigate pursuing an agreement like this with PECO.  Lowering energy prices through a group purchase in conjunction with switching to REC powered electricity would really allow for a wider market signal in favor of renewables without a big cost increase.</li>\n	<li><b>Virtual net metering/community renewables\n</b>DC recently passed a community renewables energy act giving utility rate payers access to virtual net-metering. Virtual net-metering permits anyone to subscribe to a solar installation. Once they have done so, the electricity produced by their portion of the solar installation is credited to their monthly electric bill.  More <a href=\"http://www.dcsun.org/community-renewables-energy-act-of-2013/\">here</a>.  This has not come into effect yet, but the relevant agency is in final rulemaking.  What is really cool about this is it offers an opportunity for low income renters (for example) to participate by investing in solar facilities, and the design of this (last I heard) contemplated assistance for low income families so all could participate in a sustainable future as buyers, builders, and investors.  DC\'s effort is locally focused, so all the installations that produce energy have to be located in the city, producing local jobs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>2. Strengthen incentives for energy efficient &amp; renewable improvements</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/statelocalclimate/local/showcase/student-conservation-corps.html\">Student Conservation Corps: Building a New Energy Foundation</a> - EPA &amp; West Chester Area School District - $300k project cost, $281k saved annually on electric bill. Let\'s do this in Philly! We can\n<ul>\n	<li>Save energy and money desperately needed for education</li>\n	<li>Train students for jobs in weatherization &amp; energy efficiency</li>\n	<li>Train students for jobs as solar panel installers</li>\n	<li>Outreach and weatherization projects for low income homeowners</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>3. Strengthen disclosure requirements for commercial &amp; residential buildings</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li>R<b>esidential energy use disclosure ordinance</b>\nAustin has instituted an <a href=\"http://austinenergy.com/wps/portal/ae/programs/ecad-ordinance/energy-conservation-audit-and-disclosure-ordinance/%21ut/p/a1/jZAxT8MwFIR_S4eMjo0rwGUzpgqhlEykIUvlJq-OpdSObKcR_HpSWChqoW876bt7usMlLnBp5F4rGbQ1sj3o8mZNKKOPgtA0uaWM8ETcL67zl6sZIyPw9hPI5tkDSfMs59lCkERML_SfOU7-8z9d8IC6pVgqXHYyNEibrcUFGHDqHVXWeHD7r7ZI9rUOSJoa1dpXrfW9A2RdrY00FRyCuNlM2RjkYAsOXNy7caEmhM7fRSQiwzDEylrVQlzZXUROWRrrAy6OSbzC5V81-Jz-Bk7s_A2cH7LbvRYfz7BiYZZqPpl8AjKatdw%21/dl5/d5/L2dBISEvZ0FBIS9nQSEh/\">Energy Conservation Audit &amp; Disclosure Ordinance</a> that requires homebuyers to disclose the energy use of their home through an audit.  This provides information to prospective buyers on the home\'s energy purchase.  By getting the information out there in relation to the purchase process, this is an important step towards moving to a real estate appraisal process that actually incorporates energy performance.  By over time allowing homebuyers to make decisions that lead to sale prices that are higher due to efficiency features, future appraisals can start to incorporate these market comps into play.  ACEEE has a policy brief here.  If we can make it easier for the market to reflect the increased values of residential properties that have renewable/energy efficient features, that provides even more motivation for homeowners to upgrade.  As a potential policy, this could always be designed to minimize the impact on low income households by making audits free for certain income thresholds.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>2. Consider financing mechanisms for green projects that address market failures.</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><b>Sustainable Energy Utility\n</b>The <a href=\"https://www.dcseu.com/about-dcseu\">DC Sustainable Energy Utility</a> is a private company under contract to the District Department of the Environment, which administers rebates that are funded by a Sustainable Energy Trust Fund, financed by a tax on all electric and natural gas utility ratepayers.  Rather than rely on different utilities offering different incentives, DC SEU sort of offers them all, with a very user friendly interface to homeowners.  It has gotten some rave reviews already and could be a model for Philadelphia.  This hypothetical entity could help to address the challenges in coordinating energy retrofits.<b>\n</b></li>\n	<li><b>PennSEF &amp; FREE\n</b>The Pennsylvania Sustainable Energy Finance program is a partnership between the PA Treasury Dept and FREE (the Foundation for Renewable Energy &amp; Environment), to provide technical and legal assistance, as well as low-cost capital, for energy improvement projects by municipalities, universities, schools and hospitals. More <a href=\"http://freefutures.org/pennsef/about\">here</a>.</li>\n	<li><b>Green Bank</b>\nNew York State has recently started a <a href=\"http://greenbank.ny.gov/About/Overview\">green bank</a> that invests in green flavored projects of many types, seeking to put capital in play where private markets are unwilling to do so and establish proven models to facilitate private investment, as NRDC details on this blog <a href=\"http://switchboard.nrdc.org/blogs/dsims/first_new_york_green_bank_deal.html\">post</a>.  <a href=\"http://www.ctcleanenergy.com/\">Connecticut</a> also has one.  I know of at least one county that is considering doing a green bank on the local level.  I think the next mayor could pursue this idea, either in terms of talking with the state to implement one at a statewide level (the best way forward), or possibly implementing a local version.</li>\n	<li><b>Commercial PACE</b>\nIt would be great to see the next mayor advocate with the state for Commercial PACE enabling legislation so it is easier for commercial buildings to finance retrofits through property assessments.  <a href=\"http://www.pacenow.org/make-pace-happen/\">PA is one of only 22 states without enabling legislation</a>, and every state to our Northeast (including NJ and NY) has it - but that is a bit out of the mayor\'s direct control.</li>\n</ul>\nCurious about the fossil fuel energy hub and why we oppose it? <a href=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/02/23/what-is-the-energy-hub-and-why-do-we-oppose-it/\" target=\"_blank\">Read on</a>.\n\nHow do we intend to power ourselves if we\'re rejecting fossil fuels? From web <a href=\"http://www.energyjustice.net/solutions\">page</a> of a local group (Energy Justice Network),\n<blockquote>\"When it comes to materials management, the simplified solution can be summed up as the three R\'s -- Reduce, Reuse, Recycle. These are in priority order.  The equivalent in the energy world is Conservation, Efficiency and Clean Renewables\".</blockquote>\nSee their <a href=\"http://www.energyjustice.net/files/technologies.pdf\">one page chart</a> for recommended hierarchy of waste management &amp; energy production (from cleanest to dirtiest). So when we speak of clean energy, we aren\'t just talking about solar panels; implied is Conservation, Efficiency, and then Clean Renewable Energy like Solar &amp; Wind.\n\nAs to whether we can actually power ourselves by solar &amp; wind, see <a href=\"http://thesolutionsproject.org/#tsp-section-map\">this infographic by the Solutions Project</a>, and zoom into PA. The data is from a Stanford University research. They\'re actively developing a more detailed roadmap for New York State.\n<h3>Some local proposals</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li><b><a href=\"https://www.ecasavesenergy.org/ecas-recommendations-next-mayor-philadelphia\" target=\"_blank\">ECA\'s Recommendations for the Next Mayor of Philadelphia</a>: </b>UNLEASH THE POWER OF ENERGY EFFICIENCY TO GROW PHILADELPHIA’S ECONOMY AND CREATE LOCAL JOBS<a href=\"https://www.ecasavesenergy.org/ecas-recommendations-next-mayor-philadelphia\">\n</a>A lot of the energy efficiency (EE) work will pay for itself within a year or two.  We\'ve heard about a suburban school implementing EE and saving 40% of their energy cost, which could go right back into the school budget. Would love to see this for PHL schools.</li>\n	<li><b>Philadelphia</b><strong>\'s GreenWorks</strong> program, and the <a href=\"//www.google.com/url?q=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.phila.gov%2Fgreen%2FPDFs%2FGreenworksprogressreport.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">2014 progress report</a>\nMayor Nutter\'s GreenWorks plan. The City\'s met quite a few of the targets. But in terms of energy, we haven\'t met the first target (T1). We need to reach the 5 energy targets, and develop an 80% by 2050 plan like other cities, possibly dubbing it Greenworks+.</li>\n	<li>Mayor-Elect Kenney\'s Environment policy, found here.</li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/local/essayworks/77323-a-renewable-energy-alternative-to-philadelphias-fossil-fuel-vision\">A renewable-energy alternative to Philadelphia’s fossil fuel vision</a>, excerpts below\n<blockquote>According to <a href=\"http://www.nrel.gov/docs/fy08osti/42306.pdf\">National Renewable Energy Laboratory</a> data, the Philadelphia region has the potential to install 8,700 megawatts of rooftop solar — equal to about 25 percent of the region\'s energy usage. Over 20 years, this equates to $1.3 billion annually in direct economic activity and $1.95 billion annually in indirect economic benefits for the Philadelphia area. Philadelphia could potentially get about 5 percent of this <a href=\"http://pv.energytrend.com/knowledge/Energy_Solar_USA.html\">economic activity</a>, or about $97.5 million, in the form of property, sales and wage taxes. By 2035, solar energy could annually provide more than 4,000 direct, well-paid jobs to local workers.</blockquote>\n<blockquote>Energy efficiency is also a key part of turning our city into a renewable energy hub. Efficiency like weatherization has immediate environmental, health and climate benefits, saves people money on electricity bills, and provides many local construction jobs. Jobs in energy efficiency can take advantage of the existing local workforce, and the work is much more job intensive than the natural gas industry. The <a href=\"http://www.energywisepa.org/sites/energywisepa.org/files/ACEEE%20Report.PDF\">American Council for an Energy-Efficient Economy completed a study</a> in 2009 that found that with the right policies, installation of energy efficiency and solar measures could spur the growth of at least 9,000 jobs in Philadelphia by 2025.</blockquote>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3><b>On Transportation</b></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://issuu.com/bicyclecoalition/docs/bettermobility012215.final/11?e=15252922/11076193\">Better Mobility - Philadelphia 2015</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://bicyclecoalition.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/SaferStreets.Final_.12.5.141.pdf\">Safer Streets</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><b>On Fiscal Transparency </b></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>Increase fiscal transparency and making metrics available online. <a href=\"http://nextcity.org/daily/entry/open-data-pittsburgh\">This article</a> highlights how Pittsburgh and NYC have very inexpensively made their budgets easy to use online.  Could be used for energy, as recommended by the ECA, to track energy consumption patterns.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3></h3>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3><strong>Health Impacts</strong></h3>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/p93falr\">The White House wants to explore how climate change makes you sick</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h4><strong>Policy</strong></h4>\n<ul>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/np777x9\">Switching to 100% renewables by 2050 would save major fossil economies $500 billion\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/q2aqkwq\">Solar Panels Or Greenery Required For Every New Building Rooftop In France\n</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m85cu5s\">Teens\' climate-change suit hits court with call to protect our air</a></li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>','Policy','','inherit','open','open','','29-autosave-v1','','','2015-05-30 21:09:00','2015-05-31 01:09:00','',29,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/29-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(298,2,'2015-05-28 21:16:03','2015-05-29 01:16:03','<strong> </strong>\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>“Going green” is about transitioning to a healthier, cleaner, more livable city, while growing stable, living wage jobs and opportunities for all, built on proven, readily available, clean energy technologies. In contrast, the dirty fossil fuel “Energy Hub” plan is about turning back the clock to the 19th century, and writing off our city as an environmental “sacrifice zone” for the short-term profit of some of the worst corporate polluters on the planet.\r\n\r\nCurious about the fossil fuel energy hub and why we oppose it? Read on.\r\n<h3><strong>RESOURCES</strong>\r\n<strong>Health Impacts</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/p93falr\">The White House wants to explore how climate change makes you sick</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Policy</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/np777x9\">Switching to 100% renewables by 2050 would save major fossil economies $500 billion\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/q2aqkwq\">Solar Panels Or Greenery Required For Every New Building Rooftop In France\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m85cu5s\">Teens\' climate-change suit hits court with call to protect our air</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','Policy','','inherit','open','open','','29-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:16:03','2015-05-29 01:16:03','',29,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/29-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(299,2,'2015-02-23 21:16:13','2015-02-24 02:16:13','Phil Rinaldi\'s “Energy Hub” plan will introduce more pipelines, oil trains, and refineries to Philadelphia. In short, it will re-industrialize Philadelphia. Phil Rinaldi is the head of Philadelphia Energy Solutions, the corporation responsible for 72% of the toxic air pollution in Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nFor a good summary of what this plan might mean to Philadelphia, check out Grid Magazine’s expose in their February 2015 issue titled <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/2/25/haunted-by-an-industrial-future.html\" target=\"_blank\">Haunted by an Industrial Future</a>.\r\n\r\nRinaldi’s vision of Philadelphia as an “Energy Hub” is essentially a plan for doubling down on the transport of dirty, dangerous fossil fuel products through Philadelphia in order to process it for sale either domestically or overseas. The \"Energy Hub\" is a corporate agenda currently being worked out in secretive meetings that are closed to the public and, for the most part, even the media. While we applaud the city of Philadelphia\'s commitment to sustainability through policies like Greenworks, we strongly oppose Rinaldi\'s plan as undemocratic and a step in the wrong direction for the future of our city.\r\n<h3>THE RISK FROM “OIL BOMB” TRAINS</h3>\r\nUnbeknownst to many people, Philadelphia already has two or three trains, over a mile long, carrying some of the most volatile fuels known through densely populated neighborhoods every day. These trains consist primarily of outdated tank cars, officially known as <a href=\"http://dot111.info/\" target=\"_blank\">DOT111 cars</a>, that were designed for products like corn oil, and were never meant to carry explosive loads. Also known by such colorful names as “rolling pepsi cans,” and “the Ford Pintos of the rails” these cars are unstable and prone to derail and explode, <a href=\"http://www.motherjones.com/environment/2014/05/oil-tank-trains-bakken-crude-accidents\" target=\"_blank\">causing massive damage and loss of life</a>.\r\n\r\nTo make matters worse, these “bomb trains” roll through our city daily, over a crumbling rail infrastructure, and particularly over unsafe, poorly maintained bridges. This has already led to <a href=\"http://ucreview.com/shale-oil-trains-bring-danger-to-philadelphia-p5508-112.htm\" target=\"_blank\">two recent near misses</a>. The industry goes to great lengths to hide the facts about these “oil bomb” trains, but it is very hard to hide when the inevitable happens. See <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-02-23/news/59390938_1_oil-trains-open-records-plans\" target=\"_blank\">Oil-train accidents raise concern in Phila</a>, in the February 23rd 2015 Inquirer.\r\n<h3>PUBLIC HEALTH RISKS</h3>\r\nThe Rinaldi plan also means more pipelines, more pollution-belching factories, more toxic fumes, and more asthma and lung disease in a city already plagued by an <a href=\"http://www.portal.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt?open=514&amp;objID=557612&amp;mode=2\" target=\"_blank\">epidemic of these ailments</a>. The Energy Hub not only represents a public health risk to Philadelphia. The means of obtaining the toxic gas and oil that will flow through our area also poses a risk to people who live in “fracking country,” our fellow Pennsylvanians and people from other states. See PDF titled <a href=\"http://www.lwvny.org/advocacy/issues/2011/HydraulicFracturing_060211.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Public Hearing on the Health Impacts of Hydraulic Fracturing Techniques (PDF)</a>\r\n<h3>HOW ABOUT PIPELINES?</h3>\r\nDespite the proven health risks, pipelines are touted as a “safer” way to move gas and oil, but to some, pipelines are just a way of hiding the danger underground. What constitutes “safe” to the industry is not always what the actual human beings in the path of these pipelines might consider safe. The danger is to our entire region, not just Philadelphia. See <a href=\"http://www.lwvny.org/advocacy/issues/2011/HydraulicFracturing_060211.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Opposition greets proposed Marcellus Shale-Trenton pipeline</a>.\r\n<h3>CLIMATE IMPACTS</h3>\r\nAnother important thing to know about Phillip Rinaldi is that he is on record as a climate denier, as explicitly stated in a February 6, 2015 interview with Philadelphia Business Journal (PBJ).\r\n<blockquote>PBJ: Some people say we should take advantage of the natural gas resource to get to renewables. Others say we should just invest fully in renewables. What\'s your view on either of those?\r\n\r\nPR: This is America, people are entitled to their views no matter how idiotic they are. And they are idiotic indeed. … It\'s driven by crazy science. Someone who said that we\'re killing the world and \'gee, if you would only stop burning carbon, the world won\'t die.\' I don\'t think there\'s any evidence that that\'s the case. I don\'t think it\'s very practical.</blockquote>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/morning_roundup/2015/02/q-a-with-phil-rinaldi-on-philadelphia-as-an-energy.html?page=all\" target=\"_blank\">View Full Interview</a>\r\n\r\nBecome a part of a <em>Bright Philly Future</em>. <a href=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/get-involved/\" target=\"_blank\">Join the Conversation</a>.','What is the energy hub and why do we oppose it?','','publish','open','open','','what-is-the-energy-hub-and-why-do-we-oppose-it','','\nhttp://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/get-involved/','2015-05-28 23:18:34','2015-05-29 03:18:34','',0,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/?p=299',0,'post','',0),(300,2,'2015-05-28 21:28:55','2015-05-29 01:28:55','Phil Rinaldi\'s “Energy Hub” plan will introduce more pipelines, oil trains, and refineries to Philadelphia. In short, it will re-industrialize Philadelphia. Phil Rinaldi is the head of <a href=\"http://pes-companies.com\" target=\"_blank\">Philadelphia Energy Solutions</a>, the corporation responsible for 72% of the toxic air pollution in Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nFor a good summary of what this plan might mean to Philadelphia, check out Grid Magazine’s expose in their February 2015 issue titled <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/2/25/haunted-by-an-industrial-future.html\" target=\"_blank\">Haunted by an Industrial Future</a>.\r\n\r\nRinaldi’s vision of Philadelphia as an “Energy Hub” is essentially a plan for doubling down on the transport of dirty, dangerous fossil fuel products through Philadelphia in order to process it for sale either domestically or overseas. The \"Energy Hub\" is a corporate agenda currently being worked out in secretive meetings that are closed to the public and, for the most part, even the media. While we applaud the city of Philadelphia\'s commitment to sustainability through policies like Greenworks, we strongly oppose Rinaldi\'s plan as undemocratic and a step in the wrong direction for the future of our city.\r\n\r\nTHE RISK FROM “OIL BOMB” TRAINS\r\n\r\nUnbeknownst to many people, Philadelphia already has two or three trains, over a mile long, carrying some of the most volatile fuels known through densely populated neighborhoods every day. These trains consist primarily of outdated tank cars, officially known as <a href=\"http://dot111.info/\" target=\"_blank\">DOT111 cars</a>, that were designed for products like corn oil, and were never meant to carry explosive loads. Also known by such colorful names as “rolling pepsi cans,” and “the Ford Pintos of the rails” these cars are unstable and prone to derail and explode, <a href=\"http://www.motherjones.com/environment/2014/05/oil-tank-trains-bakken-crude-accidents\" target=\"_blank\">causing massive damage and loss of life</a>.\r\n\r\nTo make matters worse, these “bomb trains” roll through our city daily, over a crumbling rail infrastructure, and particularly over unsafe, poorly maintained bridges. This has already led to <a href=\"http://ucreview.com/shale-oil-trains-bring-danger-to-philadelphia-p5508-112.htm\" target=\"_blank\">two recent near misses</a>. The industry goes to great lengths to hide the facts about these “oil bomb” trains, but it is very hard to hide when the inevitable happens. See <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-02-23/news/59390938_1_oil-trains-open-records-plans\" target=\"_blank\">Oil-train accidents raise concern in Phila</a>, in the February 23rd 2015 Inquirer.\r\n\r\nPUBLIC HEALTH RISKS\r\n\r\nThe Rinaldi plan also means more pipelines, more pollution-belching factories, more toxic fumes, and more asthma and lung disease in a city already plagued by an <a href=\"http://www.portal.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt?open=514&amp;objID=557612&amp;mode=2\" target=\"_blank\">epidemic of these ailments</a>. The Energy Hub not only represents a public health risk to Philadelphia. The means of obtaining the toxic gas and oil that will flow through our area also poses a risk to people who live in “fracking country,” our fellow Pennsylvanians and people from other states. See PDF titled <a href=\"http://www.lwvny.org/advocacy/issues/2011/HydraulicFracturing_060211.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Public Hearing on the Health Impacts of Hydraulic Fracturing Techniques (PDF)</a>\r\n\r\nHOW ABOUT PIPELINES?\r\n\r\nDespite the proven health risks, pipelines are touted as a “safer” way to move gas and oil, but to some, pipelines are just a way of hiding the danger underground. What constitutes “safe” to the industry is not always what the actual human beings in the path of these pipelines might consider safe. The danger is to our entire region, not just Philadelphia. See <a href=\"http://www.lwvny.org/advocacy/issues/2011/HydraulicFracturing_060211.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Opposition greets proposed Marcellus Shale-Trenton pipeline</a>.\r\n\r\nCLIMATE IMPACTS\r\n\r\nAnother important thing to know about Phillip Rinaldi is that he is on record as a climate denier, as explicitly stated in a February 6, 2015 interview with Philadelphia Business Journal (PBJ).\r\n<blockquote>PBJ: Some people say we should take advantage of the natural gas resource to get to renewables. Others say we should just invest fully in renewables. What\'s your view on either of those?\r\n\r\nPR: This is America, people are entitled to their views no matter how idiotic they are. And they are idiotic indeed. … It\'s driven by crazy science. Someone who said that we\'re killing the world and \'gee, if you would only stop burning carbon, the world won\'t die.\' I don\'t think there\'s any evidence that that\'s the case. I don\'t think it\'s very practical.</blockquote>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/morning_roundup/2015/02/q-a-with-phil-rinaldi-on-philadelphia-as-an-energy.html?page=all\" target=\"_blank\">View Full Interview</a>\r\n\r\nBecome a part of a <em>Bright Philly Future</em>. <a href=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/get-involved/\" target=\"_blank\">Join the Conversation</a>.','What is the energy hub and why do we oppose it?','','inherit','open','open','','299-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:28:55','2015-05-29 01:28:55','',299,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/299-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(301,2,'2015-05-28 21:31:47','2015-05-29 01:31:47','&nbsp;\r\n<table>\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>“Going green” is about transitioning to a healthier, cleaner, more livable city, while growing stable, living wage jobs and opportunities for all, built on proven, readily available, clean energy technologies. In contrast, the dirty fossil fuel “Energy Hub” plan is about turning back the clock to the 19th century, and writing off our city as an environmental “sacrifice zone” for the short-term profit of some of the worst corporate polluters on the planet.Curious about the fossil fuel energy hub and why we oppose it? <a href=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/02/23/what-is-the-energy-hub-and-why-do-we-oppose-it/\" target=\"_blank\">Read on</a>.\r\n<h3><strong>RESOURCES</strong>\r\n<strong>Health Impacts</strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/p93falr\">The White House wants to explore how climate change makes you sick</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Policy</strong></h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/np777x9\">Switching to 100% renewables by 2050 would save major fossil economies $500 billion\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/q2aqkwq\">Solar Panels Or Greenery Required For Every New Building Rooftop In France\r\n</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"http://tinyurl.com/m85cu5s\">Teens\' climate-change suit hits court with call to protect our air</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>','Policy','','inherit','open','open','','29-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:31:47','2015-05-29 01:31:47','',29,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/29-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(302,2,'2015-05-28 21:33:18','2015-05-29 01:33:18','Phil Rinaldi\'s “Energy Hub” plan will introduce more pipelines, oil trains, and refineries to Philadelphia. In short, it will re-industrialize Philadelphia. Phil Rinaldi is the head of <a href=\"http://pes-companies.com\" target=\"_blank\">Philadelphia Energy Solutions</a>, the corporation responsible for 72% of the toxic air pollution in Philadelphia.\r\n\r\nFor a good summary of what this plan might mean to Philadelphia, check out Grid Magazine’s expose in their February 2015 issue titled <a href=\"http://www.gridphilly.com/grid-magazine/2015/2/25/haunted-by-an-industrial-future.html\" target=\"_blank\">Haunted by an Industrial Future</a>.\r\n\r\nRinaldi’s vision of Philadelphia as an “Energy Hub” is essentially a plan for doubling down on the transport of dirty, dangerous fossil fuel products through Philadelphia in order to process it for sale either domestically or overseas. The \"Energy Hub\" is a corporate agenda currently being worked out in secretive meetings that are closed to the public and, for the most part, even the media. While we applaud the city of Philadelphia\'s commitment to sustainability through policies like Greenworks, we strongly oppose Rinaldi\'s plan as undemocratic and a step in the wrong direction for the future of our city.\r\n<h3>THE RISK FROM “OIL BOMB” TRAINS</h3>\r\nUnbeknownst to many people, Philadelphia already has two or three trains, over a mile long, carrying some of the most volatile fuels known through densely populated neighborhoods every day. These trains consist primarily of outdated tank cars, officially known as <a href=\"http://dot111.info/\" target=\"_blank\">DOT111 cars</a>, that were designed for products like corn oil, and were never meant to carry explosive loads. Also known by such colorful names as “rolling pepsi cans,” and “the Ford Pintos of the rails” these cars are unstable and prone to derail and explode, <a href=\"http://www.motherjones.com/environment/2014/05/oil-tank-trains-bakken-crude-accidents\" target=\"_blank\">causing massive damage and loss of life</a>.\r\n\r\nTo make matters worse, these “bomb trains” roll through our city daily, over a crumbling rail infrastructure, and particularly over unsafe, poorly maintained bridges. This has already led to <a href=\"http://ucreview.com/shale-oil-trains-bring-danger-to-philadelphia-p5508-112.htm\" target=\"_blank\">two recent near misses</a>. The industry goes to great lengths to hide the facts about these “oil bomb” trains, but it is very hard to hide when the inevitable happens. See <a href=\"http://articles.philly.com/2015-02-23/news/59390938_1_oil-trains-open-records-plans\" target=\"_blank\">Oil-train accidents raise concern in Phila</a>, in the February 23rd 2015 Inquirer.\r\n<h3>PUBLIC HEALTH RISKS</h3>\r\nThe Rinaldi plan also means more pipelines, more pollution-belching factories, more toxic fumes, and more asthma and lung disease in a city already plagued by an <a href=\"http://www.portal.state.pa.us/portal/server.pt?open=514&amp;objID=557612&amp;mode=2\" target=\"_blank\">epidemic of these ailments</a>. The Energy Hub not only represents a public health risk to Philadelphia. The means of obtaining the toxic gas and oil that will flow through our area also poses a risk to people who live in “fracking country,” our fellow Pennsylvanians and people from other states. See PDF titled <a href=\"http://www.lwvny.org/advocacy/issues/2011/HydraulicFracturing_060211.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Public Hearing on the Health Impacts of Hydraulic Fracturing Techniques (PDF)</a>\r\n<h3>HOW ABOUT PIPELINES?</h3>\r\nDespite the proven health risks, pipelines are touted as a “safer” way to move gas and oil, but to some, pipelines are just a way of hiding the danger underground. What constitutes “safe” to the industry is not always what the actual human beings in the path of these pipelines might consider safe. The danger is to our entire region, not just Philadelphia. See <a href=\"http://www.lwvny.org/advocacy/issues/2011/HydraulicFracturing_060211.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Opposition greets proposed Marcellus Shale-Trenton pipeline</a>.\r\n<h3>CLIMATE IMPACTS</h3>\r\nAnother important thing to know about Phillip Rinaldi is that he is on record as a climate denier, as explicitly stated in a February 6, 2015 interview with Philadelphia Business Journal (PBJ).\r\n<blockquote>PBJ: Some people say we should take advantage of the natural gas resource to get to renewables. Others say we should just invest fully in renewables. What\'s your view on either of those?\r\n\r\nPR: This is America, people are entitled to their views no matter how idiotic they are. And they are idiotic indeed. … It\'s driven by crazy science. Someone who said that we\'re killing the world and \'gee, if you would only stop burning carbon, the world won\'t die.\' I don\'t think there\'s any evidence that that\'s the case. I don\'t think it\'s very practical.</blockquote>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/morning_roundup/2015/02/q-a-with-phil-rinaldi-on-philadelphia-as-an-energy.html?page=all\" target=\"_blank\">View Full Interview</a>\r\n\r\nBecome a part of a <em>Bright Philly Future</em>. <a href=\"http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/get-involved/\" target=\"_blank\">Join the Conversation</a>.','What is the energy hub and why do we oppose it?','','inherit','open','open','','299-revision-v1','','','2015-05-28 21:33:18','2015-05-29 01:33:18','',299,'http://brightphillyfuture.bowersad.com/index.php/2015/05/28/299-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(303,2,'2015-05-28 21:47:15','2015-05-29 01:47:15','<h4>Where does your passion for social and environmental justice lead you?</h4>\nIf you can answer Yes to any of these, you’re needed on our team!\n<ul>\n	<li>Are you an activist who can participate in neighborhood or city-wide events, show up, canvass, make calls, involve your neighborhood organization, faith community, student or civic group?</li>\n	<li>Are you a green energy or conservation professional or business owner with services to offer?</li>\n	<li>Are you a health or legal professional, a scientist, policy analyst, social media whiz, artist or investor concerned about these issues and willing to bring your skills to the table?</li>\n</ul>\nDid we miss anything? Just let us know and we will be happy to talk with you about it.\n\n<strong>CALL US:</strong>  We want to hear how fired up you are! <b>267.338.3459</b>\nA phone conversation will help us explain the current situation and where we need help, and enable us to learn a bit about you and how your skills can be applied towards building alternatives to Big Energy.\n\n<strong>EMAIL US:</strong> Our team of volunteers can be reached by writing to this address: <strong>meenal [dot] raval [at] gmail.com</strong>\nOne of us will respond promptly. Do share your phone number with us as well for a timely response.\n\n<strong>FRIEND US:</strong> On Facebook, we\'re <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">PES-PHL</span>  [need to setup]\n\n<strong>FOLLOW US:</strong> On Twitter, we\'re <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">@pes-phl</span>  [need to setup]\n\n<strong>COME FIND US:</strong> We\'re in the streets and in civic meetings, engaging with candidates, or meeting with the media.  Chances are you already know some of us.  Come to one of these upcoming events for a live connection.  The positive energy, exciting ideas and can-do enthusiasm are palpable. See our <a href=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?src=6n6v236t9qekj76i9ub41iil6c%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;ctz=America/New_York%20\" target=\"_blank\">calendar</a>, and come engage us at one of these events.\n\n<iframe style=\"border-width: 0;\" src=\"https://www.google.com/calendar/embed?showTz=0&amp;mode=AGENDA&amp;height=600&amp;wkst=1&amp;bgcolor=%23FFFFFF&amp;src=6n6v236t9qekj76i9ub41iil6c%40group.calendar.google.com&amp;color=%232F6309&amp;ctz=America%2FNew_York\" widt