\">A Platform for Reducing Emissions, Protecting Our Communities, and Creating Good Jobs for New Yorkers</a>.  </em>We particularly like their focus on reducing emissions. And involvement with unions. And would love to implement Large Building Energy Efficiency Retrofits, as explained in Chapter 2, and installing Solar on the 100 largest schools, as explained on Chapter 5.\r\n\r\nThree of the people behind the NYC effort will be speaking here in Philadelphia this Tuesday, the evening of June 2nd. We\'d like to invite all to this event, to initiate discussions about our energy future. Details below.\r\n<blockquote><strong>Event</strong>: Labor, Community &amp; the Climate Crisis: Building Alliances for Economic &amp; Environmental Justice\r\n<strong>When: </strong>Tue June 2 6:30-8:30pm - Doors open at 6:00 pm - Snacks will be provided.<strong>\r\nWhere: </strong>IBEW (International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers) Local 98, 1719 Spring Garden St, Philadelphia, PA 19130\r\n<strong>What</strong>: Learn about <strong>Climate Works for All</strong> - the groundbreaking effort out of New York City where unions, environmental and community groups have joined in coalition to create policies that will create thousands of good jobs, dramatically cut greenhouse gas emissions, promote racial justice, and make the city more resilient. Thanks to their organizing, the city government is already making important changes, and Mayor de Blasio has announced an ambitious plan for promoting economic and environmental justice.\r\n\r\nThe Climate Works for All coalition has created a 10-point platform that calls for retrofitting all of NYC\'s large buildings to be more energy efficient, installing solar panels on 100 public schools, expanding public transportation, and seven other projects. Together, these initiatives would create nearly 40,000 living wage jobs and move NYC one third of the way toward the goal of reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 80% by 2050.\r\n\r\n<strong>Who:</strong> Key leaders from NYC have generously offered to share their plans, ideas, and experience with us. We will learn about their inspiring work and discuss what we can do here in Philly.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Jon Forster</strong> -- Co-chair of the <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/pcmny\" target=\"_blank\">People\'s Climate Movement-NY</a>; Vice President of District Council 37, AFSCME (American Federation of State, County, and Municipal Employees); City Research Scientist at the Bureau of Environmental Emergency Preparedness and Response, NYC Department of Health and Mental Hygiene.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Josh Kellermann</strong> -- Senior Policy and Research Analyst at <a href=\"http://www.alignny.org\" target=\"_blank\">ALIGN: The Alliance for a Greater New York</a> (an affiliate of Jobs with Justice), and lead author of Climate Works for All: A Platform for Reducing Emissions, Protecting Our Communities, and Creating Good Jobs for New Yorkers.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Eddie Bautista</strong> -- Executive Director of the <a class=\"profileLink\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/NYCEJA\" data-gt=\"{&quot;entity_id&quot;:&quot;114566018578525&quot;,&quot;entity_path&quot;:&quot;WebEventPublicProdFeedPermalinkController&quot;}\" data-hovercard=\"/ajax/hovercard/page.php?id=114566018578525&amp;extragetparams=%7B%22directed_target_id%22%3A476676565823869%7D\">New York City Environmental Justice Alliance</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Co-sponsors</strong>: 15 Now Philadelphia; 215 People\'s Alliance; <a href=\"http://350philly.weebly.com\" target=\"_blank\">350 Philly</a>; <a href=\"http://actionunited.org\" target=\"_blank\">Action United</a>; American Vegan Society; Be the Change; <a href=\"http://breadrosesfund.org\" target=\"_blank\">Bread and Roses Community Fund</a>; Caucus of Working Educators; <a href=\"http://cleanair.org\" target=\"_blank\">Clean Air Council</a>; <a href=\"http://cleanwateraction.org\" target=\"_blank\">Clean Water Action Pennsylvania</a>; Coalition for Peace Action - Pennsylvania; <a href=\"https://eastwickfriends.wordpress.com\" target=\"_blank\">Eastwick Friends and Neighbors Coalition</a>; Eco-Justice Working Group of the Philadelphia Yearly Meeting; Faculty &amp; Staff Federation of Community College of Phila., AFT 2026, Executive Committee; Food and Water Watch-Pennsylvania; Jewish Labor Committee - Philadelphia Chapter; <a href=\"http://maypopcollective.org\" target=\"_blank\">Maypop Collective for Climate and Economic Justice</a>; PASNAP (Pennsylvania Association of Staff Nurses and Allied Professionals); Pennsylvania Alliance for Clean Water and Air; Pennsylvania Federation of the Brotherhood of Maintenance of Way Employees/International Brotherhood of Teamsters; Philadelphia Chapter of Pennsylvania Interfaith Power and Light; Philadelphia Jewish Climate Action Network; <a href=\"http://phillyjwj.org\" target=\"_blank\">Philadelphia Jobs with Justice</a>; Philadelphia MoveOn Council; <a href=\"http://www.phillynn.org/home/default.php\" target=\"_blank\">Philadelphia Neighborhood Networks</a>; PhilaPOSH (Philadelphia Project on Occupational Safety and Health); Philly Coalition of Labor Union Women; <a href=\"http://psrphila.org\" target=\"_blank\">Physicians for Social Responsibility - Philadelphia Chapter</a>; <a href=\"http://protectingourwaters.wordpress.com\" target=\"_blank\">Protecting Our Waters</a>; Put People First PA; Sierra Club Southeastern Pennsylvania Group; <a href=\"https://theshalomcenter.org\" target=\"_blank\">The Shalom Center</a>; United Autoworkers Local 1981; United Steelworkers Local 404<strong>\r\nHosts</strong>: IBEW Local 98\r\n<strong>RSVP</strong> here: <a href=\"https://june2forum.eventbrite.com/\">https://june2forum.eventbrite.com/</a>\r\n<strong>Contact</strong>: To co-sponsor or questions, Mitch Chanin | <a href=\"mailto:mitchchanin@gmail.com\"> mitchchanin@gmail.com</a></blockquote>\r\nAs you can see, it brings together quite a diverse mix of local groups. I\'m both surprised and pleased to read this quote from Ban Ki-Moon \"If we can\'t all swim together, we will sink. There is no Plan B because there is no Planet B\" in <a href=\"http://stewartacuff.com/june2/\" target=\"_blank\">this</a> post.\r\n--','Transparency about our energy future','','inherit','open','open','','336-revision-v1','','','2015-05-31 20:06:14','2015-06-01 00:06:14','',336,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/index.php/2015/05/31/336-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(347,1,'2015-05-31 22:27:41','2015-06-01 02:27:41','','economic-justice-green-economy-featured','','inherit','open','open','','economic-justice-green-economy-featured','','','2015-05-31 22:27:41','2015-06-01 02:27:41','',336,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/economic-justice-green-economy-featured.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(348,1,'2015-05-18 23:16:19','2015-05-19 03:16:19','The Philadelphia Streets Department <a href=\"http://philadelphiastreets.com/newsroom/news-item-detail/streets-department-improves-safety-for-people-walking-and-biking-as-part-of\" target=\"_blank\">announced today</a> that it will make a substantial improvement to it\'s bike infrastructure which includes <a href=\"http://bicyclecoalition.org/philadelphia-streets-department-announces-new-bike-facilities/\" target=\"_blank\">14 miles of new bikes lanes </a>according to the Bicycle Coalition of Greater Philadelphia which also mentioned this was a moment they have been waiting for since it has been almost a decade since the street department has announced plans to improve infrastructure for cyclists.\r\n\r\nIn addition the streets department will be repainting 19 miles of and <a href=\"http://www.bikehugger.com/post/view/whats-a-sharrow\" target=\"_blank\">sharrows</a> 36 miles of current biking facilities.  The coalition also provided a fantastic map of the plan <a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?usp=sharing&amp;mid=z6MzyWzOXaX0.k-8TKO9Cgeaw\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.\r\n\r\nRadio Times <a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/whyy-public-media/biking-philly\" target=\"_blank\">also covered</a> the announcement and the rollout of the recent and wildly successful Indego Bike Share program.   Together the two programs offer a great improvement for the bicycle options here in the city of brotherly love.  Feel free to <a href=\"http://www.billgreenlee.com/?page_id=108\" target=\"_blank\">reach out</a> to recently renominated <a href=\"http://phillyelectionresults.com/\" target=\"_blank\">City Councilman Bill Greenlee</a> to tell him how much more important that is for our city then <a href=\"http://planphilly.com/articles/2014/09/19/councilman-bill-greenlee-still-won-t-let-streets-dept-stripe-bike-lane-planned-for-22nd-st\" target=\"_blank\">any imagined problem</a> he has with traffic concerns.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Welcome to Sharrowtown','','publish','open','open','','welcome-to-sharrowtown','','\nhttp://bicyclecoalition.org/philadelphia-streets-department-announces-new-bike-facilities/','2015-06-01 00:24:33','2015-06-01 04:24:33','',0,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/?p=348',0,'post','',0),(349,1,'2015-05-31 23:48:24','2015-06-01 03:48:24','','Sharrow','','inherit','open','open','','sharrow','','','2015-05-31 23:48:24','2015-06-01 03:48:24','',348,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Sharrow.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(350,1,'2015-06-01 00:06:26','2015-06-01 04:06:26','The Philadelphia Streets Department <a href=\"http://philadelphiastreets.com/newsroom/news-item-detail/streets-department-improves-safety-for-people-walking-and-biking-as-part-of\" target=\"_blank\">announced today</a> that it will make a substantial improvement to it\'s bike infrastructure which includes <a href=\"http://bicyclecoalition.org/philadelphia-streets-department-announces-new-bike-facilities/\" target=\"_blank\">14 miles of new bikes lanes </a>according to the Bicycle Coalition of Greater Philadelphia which also mentioned this was a moment they have been waiting for since it has been almost a decade since the street department has announced plans to improve infrastructure for cyclists.\r\n\r\nIn addition the streets department will be repainting 19 miles of and <a href=\"http://www.bikehugger.com/post/view/whats-a-sharrow\" target=\"_blank\">sharrows</a> 36 miles of current biking facilities.  The coalition also provided a fantastic map of the plan <a href=\"https://www.google.com/maps/d/viewer?usp=sharing&amp;mid=z6MzyWzOXaX0.k-8TKO9Cgeaw\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.\r\n\r\nRadio Times <a href=\"https://soundcloud.com/whyy-public-media/biking-philly\" target=\"_blank\">also covered</a> the announcement and the rollout of the recent and wildly successful Indego Bike Share program.   Together the two programs offer a great improvement for the bicycle options here in the city of brotherly love.  Feel free to <a href=\"http://www.billgreenlee.com/?page_id=108\" target=\"_blank\">reach out</a> to recently renominated <a href=\"http://phillyelectionresults.com/\" target=\"_blank\">City Councilman Bill Greenlee</a> to tell him how much more important that is for our city then <a href=\"http://planphilly.com/articles/2014/09/19/councilman-bill-greenlee-still-won-t-let-streets-dept-stripe-bike-lane-planned-for-22nd-st\" target=\"_blank\">any imagined problem</a> he has with traffic concerns.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Welcome to Sharrowtown','','inherit','open','open','','348-revision-v1','','','2015-06-01 00:06:26','2015-06-01 04:06:26','',348,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/index.php/2015/06/01/348-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(351,1,'2015-05-25 12:12:42','2015-05-25 16:12:42','Big expose on oil trains in the Inqurier and <a href=\"http://www.philly.com/philly/business/Oils_secret_transit.html\">Philly.com</a> that all Bright Philly Future followers and really all of Philadelphia should read yesterday.  Like the title of the article suggests there is a great deal of terrifying truth being concealed by those who are making huge profits from fracked oil while hard working individuals and families who call Philadelphia home are exposed to huge risks.  For example\r\n<blockquote>Also, freight railroad bridges, unlike highway bridges or bridges owned by passenger train operators, are not subject to public scrutiny. The inspections of rail bridges are conducted by the railroads and the results are confidential.\r\n\r\nEven the Federal Railroad Administration doesn\'t know how many rail bridges there are, as there is no public inventory similar to the National Registry of Highway Bridges.\r\n\r\nRailroads also inspect and maintain their own tracks and determine what condition to keep them in, based on federal standards that regulate train speeds.</blockquote>\r\nGoing back to the derailment last January where a tanker containing oil dangled off the arsenal bridge over the Schuylkill river it was later found that <a href=\"http://www.newsworks.org/index.php/local/item/65376-csx-improper-maintenance-work-caused-derailment-?linktype=hp_topstory\" target=\"_blank\">poor track maintenance was to blame</a> for the accident.  Essentially our homes and communities are in the hands of these private companies which are making lots of money from fracking while we have no voice or access to information about what is going on.\r\n\r\nIt\'s an excellent story, but not for the faint of heart.  Join us in the fight against these bomb trains.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Frightening truth behind oil trains','','publish','open','open','','frighting-truth-behind-oil-trains','','','2015-06-01 13:46:17','2015-06-01 17:46:17','',0,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/?p=351',0,'post','',0),(352,1,'2015-06-01 13:45:27','2015-06-01 17:45:27','','2015-04-26 09.07.16','','inherit','open','open','','2015-04-26-09-07-16','','','2015-06-01 13:45:27','2015-06-01 17:45:27','',351,'http://www.brightphillyfuture.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2015-04-26-09.07.16.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(353,1,'201